00:00:25.755 --> 00:00:27.630
TONIO BUONASSISI: Today
we're going to talk--

00:00:27.630 --> 00:00:30.000
or it's the first
technical discussion

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:32.490
of the actual solar
cell device itself.

00:00:32.490 --> 00:00:35.140
We talked last
class about the sun

00:00:35.140 --> 00:00:37.197
and about the nature
of the solar resource.

00:00:37.197 --> 00:00:39.780
Today we're going to be talking
about the interaction of light

00:00:39.780 --> 00:00:40.920
with matter.

00:00:40.920 --> 00:00:44.270
In particular, we're
focusing on light absorption.

00:00:44.270 --> 00:00:47.050
This lecture could alternatively
be called "Light Not Getting

00:00:47.050 --> 00:00:50.740
Absorbed" or "Optical Losses."

00:00:50.740 --> 00:00:55.210
Both are important, and both
are related, as we'll see.

00:00:55.210 --> 00:00:58.980
So this is part of the
fundamentals of the course.

00:00:58.980 --> 00:01:01.270
Just to situate
ourselves, we're here

00:01:01.270 --> 00:01:03.645
right now in the fundamentals,
the first third of course.

00:01:03.645 --> 00:01:05.228
Then we'll talk about
the technologies

00:01:05.228 --> 00:01:06.490
and the cross-cutting themes.

00:01:06.490 --> 00:01:07.906
And what we're
going to talk about

00:01:07.906 --> 00:01:10.330
is extremely important
because it allows us

00:01:10.330 --> 00:01:12.430
to understand the technologies.

00:01:12.430 --> 00:01:15.500
Once we begin discussing them
and we discuss cost trade

00:01:15.500 --> 00:01:19.524
offs of implementing
this particular technique

00:01:19.524 --> 00:01:21.190
for the way for it
to absorb more light,

00:01:21.190 --> 00:01:23.920
we can appreciate how
much we can quantify

00:01:23.920 --> 00:01:27.450
the impact of that
technology development,

00:01:27.450 --> 00:01:30.232
and we could also later
on ascribe a cost to it,

00:01:30.232 --> 00:01:34.560
to determine the total
cost benefit analysis.

00:01:34.560 --> 00:01:37.840
So conversion
efficiency is really

00:01:37.840 --> 00:01:40.490
what dictates the performance
of the device, the solar cell

00:01:40.490 --> 00:01:41.550
device.

00:01:41.550 --> 00:01:46.370
It's how the solar cell device
converts sunlight, the input

00:01:46.370 --> 00:01:48.680
energy, to some usable
output energy, which

00:01:48.680 --> 00:01:51.520
is in the form of electricity,
typically, from a solar panel.

00:01:51.520 --> 00:01:53.720
so the electricity
coming out of these

00:01:53.720 --> 00:01:55.780
leads, for instance, right here.

00:01:55.780 --> 00:02:00.230
And that conversion efficiency,
that simple equation,

00:02:00.230 --> 00:02:03.340
for most solar cells, can
break down into the following.

00:02:03.340 --> 00:02:04.340
You have inputs.

00:02:04.340 --> 00:02:05.590
Sorry for the small font here.

00:02:05.590 --> 00:02:06.850
This reads solar spectrum.

00:02:06.850 --> 00:02:08.430
That's your input.

00:02:08.430 --> 00:02:11.330
Your output, which is
the charge collection,

00:02:11.330 --> 00:02:13.750
it's a collective charge
coming out of your device,

00:02:13.750 --> 00:02:16.800
and a bunch of steps in between.

00:02:16.800 --> 00:02:19.910
So from the solar spectrum,
we have to absorb that light,

00:02:19.910 --> 00:02:23.110
then we have to excite
charge within the material.

00:02:23.110 --> 00:02:25.940
Then that charge has to move
around inside the material

00:02:25.940 --> 00:02:29.210
to get to the metallic
context in the front side.

00:02:29.210 --> 00:02:32.570
Charge separation has to occur
for there to be a voltage.

00:02:32.570 --> 00:02:34.890
And finally, the charge
collection process.

00:02:34.890 --> 00:02:38.620
And so the total
efficiency of this device

00:02:38.620 --> 00:02:42.547
is the product of each of
these individual processes.

00:02:42.547 --> 00:02:44.380
And so if you're making
a solar cell device,

00:02:44.380 --> 00:02:47.450
and I know about a third of you
are based on your background

00:02:47.450 --> 00:02:51.650
surveys, this diagram right
here will ring true to you.

00:02:51.650 --> 00:02:53.940
It's Liebig's Law
of the Minimum.

00:02:53.940 --> 00:02:56.630
What this is
representing is a barrel

00:02:56.630 --> 00:02:58.820
that has water being
dripped into it.

00:02:58.820 --> 00:03:03.640
And the water will flow out
of whatever piece of wood

00:03:03.640 --> 00:03:04.930
is the shortest.

00:03:04.930 --> 00:03:07.460
And in the case of
a solar cell device,

00:03:07.460 --> 00:03:09.840
you can ascribe a
certain name to each

00:03:09.840 --> 00:03:11.280
of these pieces of wood.

00:03:11.280 --> 00:03:13.590
We'll learn what each
of those are with time.

00:03:13.590 --> 00:03:16.060
But one of the big
ones is optical losses.

00:03:16.060 --> 00:03:19.140
And the optical losses
tend to be rather severe

00:03:19.140 --> 00:03:21.019
on some of our lab scale cells.

00:03:21.019 --> 00:03:23.060
So one of the easiest ways
of boosting efficiency

00:03:23.060 --> 00:03:25.920
is simply to take care
of your optical losses

00:03:25.920 --> 00:03:29.630
and to minimize the amount of
light reflected or not absorbed

00:03:29.630 --> 00:03:32.320
into maximizing amount of
life that's actually absorbed.

00:03:32.320 --> 00:03:33.990
And so to do that,
there are a number

00:03:33.990 --> 00:03:37.005
of standard techniques and some
cutting edge research areas.

00:03:37.005 --> 00:03:38.880
And I'll attempt to give
you a broad overview

00:03:38.880 --> 00:03:41.180
and survey of both,
assuming, of course,

00:03:41.180 --> 00:03:43.900
you've done your
background reading.

00:03:43.900 --> 00:03:46.540
So the learning
objectives, the first

00:03:46.540 --> 00:03:48.290
is to be able to
calculate the reflectance

00:03:48.290 --> 00:03:51.940
in non-absorption optical
losses of a solar cell.

00:03:51.940 --> 00:03:54.680
So this is essentially all
the light that's not absorbed.

00:03:54.680 --> 00:03:57.590
We want to be able
to calculate that.

00:03:57.590 --> 00:04:00.360
The second is to describe
the physical underpinnings

00:04:00.360 --> 00:04:04.900
and the implementations of four
to five-- there are five here.

00:04:04.900 --> 00:04:06.790
I added one at the end.

00:04:06.790 --> 00:04:10.330
Four to five advanced methods
of reducing optical losses.

00:04:10.330 --> 00:04:12.230
So there are
technologies, techniques

00:04:12.230 --> 00:04:14.870
that we've used that we've
developed over time that we can

00:04:14.870 --> 00:04:17.079
use to minimize
the optical losses,

00:04:17.079 --> 00:04:20.430
to minimize the amount of
light reflected or not absorbed

00:04:20.430 --> 00:04:23.280
inside of a solar cell device.

00:04:23.280 --> 00:04:25.390
So to think of this
pictorially, we

00:04:25.390 --> 00:04:28.120
can come up with the
following diagram, where

00:04:28.120 --> 00:04:31.560
we have some incident energy,
in this case incident light.

00:04:31.560 --> 00:04:32.850
Here's our medium.

00:04:32.850 --> 00:04:34.767
Here's the amount of
light that gets absorbed.

00:04:34.767 --> 00:04:37.016
Here's the amount of light
that gets transmitted right

00:04:37.016 --> 00:04:39.340
through that does not get
absorbed within the material

00:04:39.340 --> 00:04:40.369
upon passing through it.

00:04:40.369 --> 00:04:41.910
And there's a certain
amount of light

00:04:41.910 --> 00:04:44.700
that just gets reflected off
the front of your solar cell

00:04:44.700 --> 00:04:45.480
device.

00:04:45.480 --> 00:04:48.900
We want to, obviously,
maximize this part right here.

00:04:53.260 --> 00:04:55.840
So to begin, we
give a quick review

00:04:55.840 --> 00:04:58.990
of light, the nature of light.

00:04:58.990 --> 00:05:02.310
This is going back to the
particle wave duality of light.

00:05:02.310 --> 00:05:04.790
It will be useful alternatively
to think about light

00:05:04.790 --> 00:05:08.240
as a particle, quant of
light, or to think about light

00:05:08.240 --> 00:05:11.380
as a wave, depending on what
light management technique

00:05:11.380 --> 00:05:13.200
we're going to be describing.

00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:16.830
And in particular, I'd
like to just highlight

00:05:16.830 --> 00:05:18.470
these equations over here.

00:05:18.470 --> 00:05:22.330
The notion that one can define
the energy of a photon coming

00:05:22.330 --> 00:05:25.250
in, and that photon has
a certain wavelength,

00:05:25.250 --> 00:05:27.460
a certain frequency, a
certain wave length associated

00:05:27.460 --> 00:05:30.510
with it-- frequency and
wavelength-- related,

00:05:30.510 --> 00:05:32.030
of course, by the
speed of light,

00:05:32.030 --> 00:05:34.970
Planck's constant, and so forth.

00:05:34.970 --> 00:05:39.100
So just to situate ourselves
with broad numbers,

00:05:39.100 --> 00:05:43.240
so when we dive in and talk
about spatial dimensions

00:05:43.240 --> 00:05:45.150
in relation to the
wavelength of the light,

00:05:45.150 --> 00:05:47.880
we're in a situation
where we can actually

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:51.250
have a horse sense, a
common sense, about it.

00:05:51.250 --> 00:05:53.490
The visible photon
wavelengths are usually

00:05:53.490 --> 00:05:54.770
in the hundreds of nanometers.

00:05:54.770 --> 00:05:57.980
And the solar spectrum
peaks somewhere around 550,

00:05:57.980 --> 00:06:00.360
just good numbers
to have in mind.

00:06:00.360 --> 00:06:03.940
So this was that solar spectrum,
the integrated solar radiance

00:06:03.940 --> 00:06:05.700
versus wavelength.

00:06:05.700 --> 00:06:10.020
And the second point
that is equally valid,

00:06:10.020 --> 00:06:14.322
we can describe the wavelengths
of the incoming light,

00:06:14.322 --> 00:06:16.030
wavelengths of the
incoming light lambda,

00:06:16.030 --> 00:06:19.390
or we can describe the energies
of the incoming light, this E

00:06:19.390 --> 00:06:21.770
sub ph, the energy
of the photons.

00:06:21.770 --> 00:06:24.410
So just to situate
ourselves again,

00:06:24.410 --> 00:06:27.830
the visible photon energies
are typically in a range of 0.6

00:06:27.830 --> 00:06:31.630
to 6 eV, electron volts,
again, with the peak

00:06:31.630 --> 00:06:34.320
of the solar spectrum at
550 nanometers, somewhere

00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:36.260
around 2.3 eV.

00:06:36.260 --> 00:06:37.430
Good.

00:06:37.430 --> 00:06:42.590
So a simple thing to keep in
mind, for those high energy

00:06:42.590 --> 00:06:44.425
particle physicists
in the room, that when

00:06:44.425 --> 00:06:45.990
we're talking about
visible light,

00:06:45.990 --> 00:06:49.390
we're interacting with a very
specific type of electron

00:06:49.390 --> 00:06:50.580
inside of our system.

00:06:50.580 --> 00:06:51.770
It's the valence electrons.

00:06:51.770 --> 00:06:54.620
These are the electrons that
are typically most loosely bound

00:06:54.620 --> 00:06:56.550
inside of a system
or I would say

00:06:56.550 --> 00:07:01.350
in the outer shells of the
atoms within the material.

00:07:01.350 --> 00:07:04.140
You're typically not interacting
with core shell electrons

00:07:04.140 --> 00:07:05.320
with visible light.

00:07:05.320 --> 00:07:06.790
For that, you need x-rays.

00:07:06.790 --> 00:07:10.650
So this is just something
to keep in mind.

00:07:10.650 --> 00:07:14.125
When we start looking at
the wavelength dependence

00:07:14.125 --> 00:07:16.670
of absorption inside
of a material,

00:07:16.670 --> 00:07:20.690
you can have, for example, in
the visible range, a decreasing

00:07:20.690 --> 00:07:23.660
depth of penetration of the
light with increasing energy,

00:07:23.660 --> 00:07:25.535
whereas with x-rays,
it's the exact opposite.

00:07:25.535 --> 00:07:28.076
It's because you're dealing with
different types of electrons

00:07:28.076 --> 00:07:29.050
and the material.

00:07:29.050 --> 00:07:30.710
So just to situate
ourselves, I know

00:07:30.710 --> 00:07:33.460
we have a fair number physicists
and chemists in the room.

00:07:33.460 --> 00:07:37.750
That's a message
geared toward them.

00:07:37.750 --> 00:07:41.870
Let's describe how light
interacts with matter.

00:07:41.870 --> 00:07:45.640
And first off, come up
with a few variables.

00:07:45.640 --> 00:07:48.690
Define a few units that
will make it easier

00:07:48.690 --> 00:07:52.110
for us to understand how light
is interacting with matter.

00:07:52.110 --> 00:07:53.900
And so here what
I've done for you

00:07:53.900 --> 00:07:57.880
is placed the equation that
describes the complex index

00:07:57.880 --> 00:08:01.270
of refraction of a material.

00:08:01.270 --> 00:08:03.250
What this means,
effectively, you

00:08:03.250 --> 00:08:06.410
can think about this refractive
index of the material

00:08:06.410 --> 00:08:11.250
as being comprised of
two different components.

00:08:11.250 --> 00:08:13.584
For now, it's going
to be fairly cerebral,

00:08:13.584 --> 00:08:15.250
but I'm going to
reduce it to practicing

00:08:15.250 --> 00:08:16.760
in a couple of slides.

00:08:16.760 --> 00:08:19.020
The real component of
the refractive index--

00:08:19.020 --> 00:08:22.150
and the refractive index is
material-specific property.

00:08:22.150 --> 00:08:23.780
So if I have, for
example, silicon

00:08:23.780 --> 00:08:25.430
or if I have silicon
nitride or if I

00:08:25.430 --> 00:08:27.180
have a particular
type of glass, it'll

00:08:27.180 --> 00:08:29.770
have a particular
refractive index.

00:08:29.770 --> 00:08:31.810
It's comprised of a
real component which

00:08:31.810 --> 00:08:34.256
indicates the phase velocity
inside of the material

00:08:34.256 --> 00:08:35.630
and an imaginary
component, which

00:08:35.630 --> 00:08:37.799
can be thought of as an
extinction coefficient.

00:08:37.799 --> 00:08:40.360
And it is related
to the attenuation

00:08:40.360 --> 00:08:44.690
of the light intensity as it
travels through that material.

00:08:44.690 --> 00:08:47.700
The measurements for those who
have already taken measurements

00:08:47.700 --> 00:08:50.450
before on a spectroscopic
ellipsometer, this

00:08:50.450 --> 00:08:53.921
is how you measure that
parameter up there.

00:08:53.921 --> 00:08:55.670
We don't have to dive
too deeply into that

00:08:55.670 --> 00:08:56.970
for the purposes of the class.

00:08:56.970 --> 00:08:59.340
It's just for background.

00:08:59.340 --> 00:09:02.700
Why these values are
important-- these values

00:09:02.700 --> 00:09:05.450
here describe the interaction
of light inside of a medium,

00:09:05.450 --> 00:09:07.160
inside of a material.

00:09:07.160 --> 00:09:09.410
And we use that
information to calculate

00:09:09.410 --> 00:09:12.700
engineering relevant parameters
such as reflectance of light

00:09:12.700 --> 00:09:14.410
off of a surface.

00:09:14.410 --> 00:09:17.920
So if we want to calculate what
is the reflectance of light off

00:09:17.920 --> 00:09:20.780
of the silicon right
here, I can calculate it

00:09:20.780 --> 00:09:22.550
by knowing these
properties right here,

00:09:22.550 --> 00:09:25.260
by knowing the real and
imaginary components

00:09:25.260 --> 00:09:30.140
of the refractive index
of silicon, in this case.

00:09:30.140 --> 00:09:32.060
And the reason
that's important is

00:09:32.060 --> 00:09:35.280
because we want to minimize
reflection off of surfaces.

00:09:35.280 --> 00:09:37.000
So I've come up with
the first equation

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:40.850
right here which is describing
the reflectance from air

00:09:40.850 --> 00:09:43.530
to a solid, in this
case, from air where

00:09:43.530 --> 00:09:46.540
the refractive index
is 1 to a solid,

00:09:46.540 --> 00:09:48.720
namely, say for example,
silicon right here

00:09:48.720 --> 00:09:53.160
or glass, which has a finite
refractive index typically

00:09:53.160 --> 00:09:54.750
greater than 1.

00:09:54.750 --> 00:09:57.750
And so I have an equation here
that describes the reflectance.

00:09:57.750 --> 00:09:59.390
Let me dive a little
deeper into it

00:09:59.390 --> 00:10:01.050
and try to understand
what exactly

00:10:01.050 --> 00:10:03.290
that equation is telling me.

00:10:03.290 --> 00:10:07.170
So from the folks who have
studied mechanics, many of you

00:10:07.170 --> 00:10:09.190
are mechanical
engineers in the room,

00:10:09.190 --> 00:10:11.820
you may recall studying a
problem wherein you have

00:10:11.820 --> 00:10:14.130
two springs that are connected.

00:10:14.130 --> 00:10:16.390
They have different
spring constants,

00:10:16.390 --> 00:10:18.330
different stiffnesses,
shall we say.

00:10:18.330 --> 00:10:19.830
And you excite a wave over here.

00:10:19.830 --> 00:10:20.840
It travels down.

00:10:20.840 --> 00:10:22.930
And when it reaches the
interface between the two,

00:10:22.930 --> 00:10:24.346
part of the wave
is reflected back

00:10:24.346 --> 00:10:26.140
and part continues through.

00:10:26.140 --> 00:10:29.900
The speed of the
wave is changing

00:10:29.900 --> 00:10:31.810
as it goes from one
spring to the other,

00:10:31.810 --> 00:10:34.530
because the stiffness is
changing of the springs.

00:10:34.530 --> 00:10:37.670
And the amount reflected can
be described by this equation

00:10:37.670 --> 00:10:40.250
right here, which looks
awfully like the equation

00:10:40.250 --> 00:10:42.810
right above it, which is
describing the amount of light

00:10:42.810 --> 00:10:44.320
reflected off of an interface.

00:10:44.320 --> 00:10:49.500
And in reality, those ends have
a very similar meaning, the n

00:10:49.500 --> 00:10:50.270
and the z.

00:10:50.270 --> 00:10:51.770
The n, in the case
of light, which

00:10:51.770 --> 00:10:53.783
is the real components
of the refractive index.

00:10:53.783 --> 00:10:57.710
Mind you, this
parameter right here,

00:10:57.710 --> 00:10:59.460
this indicates phase
velocity in material.

00:10:59.460 --> 00:11:02.500
It could also be
thought of very loosely

00:11:02.500 --> 00:11:04.980
as the ability of an
electromagnetic wave coming

00:11:04.980 --> 00:11:08.280
into material to slosh
those electrons around.

00:11:08.280 --> 00:11:09.890
Not exactly a
stiffness coefficient,

00:11:09.890 --> 00:11:13.100
but it bears some
rough resemblance.

00:11:13.100 --> 00:11:16.350
So this is a method for
you to gain a foothold

00:11:16.350 --> 00:11:18.780
in this new area
of understanding

00:11:18.780 --> 00:11:20.820
the refractive
index of a material

00:11:20.820 --> 00:11:24.190
based on something you've
already seen before.

00:11:24.190 --> 00:11:26.660
So I would advise
taking this analogy

00:11:26.660 --> 00:11:28.770
as far as it will go
until it breaks down.

00:11:28.770 --> 00:11:30.840
Push it as far as it goes
until it breaks down.

00:11:30.840 --> 00:11:32.830
And you'll see at some
point it actually does,

00:11:32.830 --> 00:11:36.820
but it's a useful
place to start.

00:11:36.820 --> 00:11:40.020
So I'm going to ask you
a couple of questions.

00:11:40.020 --> 00:11:43.712
This might be rather
new for a lot of folks.

00:11:43.712 --> 00:11:45.420
But the purpose of
asking these questions

00:11:45.420 --> 00:11:46.500
is to get you thinking.

00:11:46.500 --> 00:11:49.110
And eventually we'll get
to a point of heightened

00:11:49.110 --> 00:11:51.860
understanding as a result.

00:11:51.860 --> 00:11:54.300
Tinted windows.

00:11:54.300 --> 00:11:57.220
So if you have a
tinted window, what

00:11:57.220 --> 00:12:00.010
is typically happening
at that tinted window?

00:12:00.010 --> 00:12:03.122
Why can't you see inside?

00:12:03.122 --> 00:12:04.580
What would you
imagine is going on?

00:12:04.580 --> 00:12:06.510
So let me go back to
this reflectance equation

00:12:06.510 --> 00:12:10.000
right here, this one.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:11.990
How would you modify
a reflectance off

00:12:11.990 --> 00:12:13.910
of a window, let's say?

00:12:13.910 --> 00:12:16.030
And let's drop the k's for now.

00:12:16.030 --> 00:12:19.350
Let's leave those aside and
just focus on this parameter

00:12:19.350 --> 00:12:21.660
right here, n minus
1 quantity squared

00:12:21.660 --> 00:12:23.560
n plus 1 quantity squared.

00:12:23.560 --> 00:12:28.110
What would increase the
reflectance off of that window,

00:12:28.110 --> 00:12:29.800
if I have a larger
n or a smaller n?

00:12:34.750 --> 00:12:38.660
If I have a bigger n, I
would get bigger reflectance.

00:12:38.660 --> 00:12:39.686
Is that right?

00:12:39.686 --> 00:12:42.851
r goes up?

00:12:42.851 --> 00:12:45.460
Well, you'd have to
plot it out, I guess.

00:12:45.460 --> 00:12:49.280
So if I change the refractive
index of the material

00:12:49.280 --> 00:12:52.175
that I am working with, I can
change the reflectivity off

00:12:52.175 --> 00:12:54.080
of that interface,
off of that surface.

00:12:54.080 --> 00:12:55.870
So if I add a
coating, for instance,

00:12:55.870 --> 00:12:59.720
to a window that increases
the reflectivity,

00:12:59.720 --> 00:13:05.600
then the amount of light that is
able to escape from the inside

00:13:05.600 --> 00:13:07.070
to my eyes decreases.

00:13:07.070 --> 00:13:10.010
Now, with normal
incident light, there

00:13:10.010 --> 00:13:11.810
is a beautiful
symmetry involved.

00:13:11.810 --> 00:13:14.710
That is, the amount
reflected off of one side

00:13:14.710 --> 00:13:18.960
is equal to the amount of light
reflected off the other side.

00:13:18.960 --> 00:13:23.830
So just the same way that
I'm losing the ability

00:13:23.830 --> 00:13:26.180
to see inside, the
folks inside are also

00:13:26.180 --> 00:13:27.740
losing the ability to see out.

00:13:27.740 --> 00:13:29.330
But they can still see out.

00:13:29.330 --> 00:13:31.090
Why is that?

00:13:31.090 --> 00:13:34.230
Why is it that with
the same reflectivity

00:13:34.230 --> 00:13:36.030
they're able to see
outside and I'm not

00:13:36.030 --> 00:13:38.321
able to see in through that
tinted window, through that

00:13:38.321 --> 00:13:41.630
car, for example, that's driving
by with the tinted glass?

00:13:41.630 --> 00:13:44.970
Why can't I see insight but they
can see out, what's going on?

00:13:44.970 --> 00:13:46.404
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:13:46.404 --> 00:13:48.070
TONIO BUONASSISI:
Yeah, I hear somebody.

00:13:48.070 --> 00:13:49.486
AUDIENCE: The light
on the outside

00:13:49.486 --> 00:13:52.256
is much stronger in terms of
an absolute amount of light

00:13:52.256 --> 00:13:53.109
being reflected.

00:13:53.109 --> 00:13:54.400
TONIO BUONASSISI: Yep, exactly.

00:13:54.400 --> 00:13:57.700
So yes, the reflectivity
as a percentage

00:13:57.700 --> 00:14:00.247
is the same for both parties.

00:14:00.247 --> 00:14:01.830
But the amount of
light, the magnitude

00:14:01.830 --> 00:14:04.280
of the light from the
outside, is much, much greater

00:14:04.280 --> 00:14:05.580
than it is on the inside.

00:14:05.580 --> 00:14:07.620
Can anybody give me
just a gut sense.

00:14:07.620 --> 00:14:10.190
If I'm outside on a sunny
day, how much brighter

00:14:10.190 --> 00:14:13.180
is it outside versus
inside right here?

00:14:13.180 --> 00:14:15.130
Factor of?

00:14:15.130 --> 00:14:17.130
AUDIENCE: 100, maybe?

00:14:17.130 --> 00:14:19.940
TONIO BUONASSISI: Maybe a factor
of 10, somewhere in that range.

00:14:19.940 --> 00:14:22.742
And so when you walk
outside on a sunny day,

00:14:22.742 --> 00:14:24.700
you'll notice your eyes
adjusting a little bit.

00:14:24.700 --> 00:14:25.727
It'll take a minute.

00:14:25.727 --> 00:14:28.060
And when we walk back inside,
it will take a minute here

00:14:28.060 --> 00:14:29.460
for your eyes to adjust as well.

00:14:29.460 --> 00:14:31.460
That's because of the
difference in intensities.

00:14:31.460 --> 00:14:33.880
So if you imagine being
outside of that car

00:14:33.880 --> 00:14:40.147
and having 10 times the amount
of light being reflected,

00:14:40.147 --> 00:14:42.480
that small amount of light
that is actually transmitting

00:14:42.480 --> 00:14:44.680
through the window from the
car to the outside world

00:14:44.680 --> 00:14:48.280
will be washed out by the
amount of reflected light.

00:14:48.280 --> 00:14:50.460
Whereas if you're
inside the car,

00:14:50.460 --> 00:14:52.636
there's a lot of light
coming through that window,

00:14:52.636 --> 00:14:54.260
even though a lot of
it gets reflected,

00:14:54.260 --> 00:14:56.177
there's still a sizable
amount coming through.

00:14:56.177 --> 00:14:57.551
And the amount of
light that gets

00:14:57.551 --> 00:14:59.700
reflected off that window
of the internal light

00:14:59.700 --> 00:15:02.540
is small in relation to
the outside light that

00:15:02.540 --> 00:15:04.360
is being transmitted
through that window.

00:15:04.360 --> 00:15:08.897
So it's important to think
about these processes,

00:15:08.897 --> 00:15:10.980
both in terms of their
reflectance as a percentage

00:15:10.980 --> 00:15:14.880
but also the magnitudes
of the light involved.

00:15:14.880 --> 00:15:17.090
What if that glass pane
was flipped around?

00:15:17.090 --> 00:15:18.195
Would it change anything?

00:15:18.195 --> 00:15:24.960
If I took that glass and just
flipped it, would it change it?

00:15:24.960 --> 00:15:28.930
What about the
symmetry argument,

00:15:28.930 --> 00:15:32.270
that the amount of light is
reflected, the r reflectance,

00:15:32.270 --> 00:15:33.935
is the same from both sides?

00:15:33.935 --> 00:15:35.643
AUDIENCE: Is it not
the case that there's

00:15:35.643 --> 00:15:37.607
a coating on the outside?

00:15:37.607 --> 00:15:41.044
So if the change
in refracted index

00:15:41.044 --> 00:15:43.324
is an abrupt change
from the outside looking

00:15:43.324 --> 00:15:43.990
at this coating.

00:15:43.990 --> 00:15:45.448
Because on the
inside, you're going

00:15:45.448 --> 00:15:48.900
through some median glass,
which is more index matched

00:15:48.900 --> 00:15:49.900
than the outside.

00:15:49.900 --> 00:15:51.350
TONIO BUONASSISI:
Yeah, so I would

00:15:51.350 --> 00:15:53.580
advise you to actually walk
through that calculation.

00:15:53.580 --> 00:15:56.361
And what you'll find is it
winds up being the same.

00:15:56.361 --> 00:15:58.610
And it's because you have
to take all reflectances off

00:15:58.610 --> 00:16:01.730
of all these interfaces
into account.

00:16:01.730 --> 00:16:05.000
There are, in fact, three
interfaces-- the air,

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:08.400
the glass; the glass, the
anti-reflection coding;

00:16:08.400 --> 00:16:10.700
and the anti-reflection
coding, the outside.

00:16:10.700 --> 00:16:14.110
This, of course, without getting
into quarter wave effects,

00:16:14.110 --> 00:16:18.480
which we'll get into
a minute, there's

00:16:18.480 --> 00:16:21.119
some higher order effects that
deal with phase change, which

00:16:21.119 --> 00:16:22.410
we haven't discussed right now.

00:16:22.410 --> 00:16:25.120
We're just assuming
that all of these layers

00:16:25.120 --> 00:16:28.960
are well above the wavelength of
the light in terms of thickness

00:16:28.960 --> 00:16:33.890
and that these equations, these
linear equations, are valid.

00:16:33.890 --> 00:16:34.670
Very good.

00:16:34.670 --> 00:16:37.800
So this is just
to get us situated

00:16:37.800 --> 00:16:39.900
with this new concept
of reflectance--

00:16:39.900 --> 00:16:43.200
and again, very
powerful equation.

00:16:43.200 --> 00:16:45.610
Keep in mind that this
is a very specific form

00:16:45.610 --> 00:16:47.491
of the reflectance from
an air into a solid.

00:16:47.491 --> 00:16:49.240
If you're going from
a solid into a solid,

00:16:49.240 --> 00:16:53.000
you'll add your n1
and your n2, depending

00:16:53.000 --> 00:17:00.030
on what material going into and
what material are coming from.

00:17:00.030 --> 00:17:04.569
So we're happy to walk through
that perhaps during recitation.

00:17:04.569 --> 00:17:06.760
OK, so what we're
going to do now

00:17:06.760 --> 00:17:09.344
is we've talked about
reflectance off of surfaces.

00:17:09.344 --> 00:17:11.510
What I'd like to do is talk
about a light absorption

00:17:11.510 --> 00:17:12.759
inside of a material.

00:17:12.759 --> 00:17:15.050
So let's imagine that through
the techniques that we're

00:17:15.050 --> 00:17:16.880
going to be discussing
later on in lecture,

00:17:16.880 --> 00:17:18.619
we manage to minimize
the amount of reflectance

00:17:18.619 --> 00:17:19.700
off the front surface.

00:17:19.700 --> 00:17:21.900
And now the light that's
incident on the material

00:17:21.900 --> 00:17:24.050
is actually going to go
inside and get absorbed

00:17:24.050 --> 00:17:25.630
by the material inside.

00:17:25.630 --> 00:17:28.390
We need to be able to understand
how light gets absorbed inside

00:17:28.390 --> 00:17:29.380
of matter.

00:17:29.380 --> 00:17:33.860
And for that, we apply a very
simple formulation inside

00:17:33.860 --> 00:17:37.000
of this class, which is called
Beer-Lambert's Law, which

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:41.630
is a very simple
yet very powerful

00:17:41.630 --> 00:17:44.320
formulation that describes not
only the interaction of light

00:17:44.320 --> 00:17:45.861
with the solar cell
material but also

00:17:45.861 --> 00:17:48.850
light through the
atmosphere, light the water,

00:17:48.850 --> 00:17:51.490
many other forms of
optical absorption.

00:17:51.490 --> 00:17:55.120
And for that, I'd like to
call Joe up for a quick demo

00:17:55.120 --> 00:17:59.690
that he put together that will
allow us to actually plot out

00:17:59.690 --> 00:18:00.980
Beer-Lambert's Law.

00:18:00.980 --> 00:18:04.180
And I'd like to start
with what I would think

00:18:04.180 --> 00:18:05.710
of as a simple hypothesis.

00:18:05.710 --> 00:18:07.485
What we're going to
be doing, and Joe

00:18:07.485 --> 00:18:09.818
will explain this a minute,
what we're going to be doing

00:18:09.818 --> 00:18:13.080
is taking many
sheets of material.

00:18:13.080 --> 00:18:15.420
This is just some
polyethylene material,

00:18:15.420 --> 00:18:16.830
a little bit discolored.

00:18:16.830 --> 00:18:20.356
And we're going to shine a laser
down on to this photodiode.

00:18:20.356 --> 00:18:21.980
The photodiode current
will be measured

00:18:21.980 --> 00:18:23.730
by this little current
meter right here.

00:18:23.730 --> 00:18:27.870
And we'll be inserting these
panes of plastic in the middle.

00:18:27.870 --> 00:18:30.590
And as we increase the
thickness of the plastic,

00:18:30.590 --> 00:18:32.190
applying good
pressure in between

00:18:32.190 --> 00:18:36.530
to minimize the reflectance,
the air gap, for instance--

00:18:36.530 --> 00:18:39.490
as we increase the thickness
of the polyethylene,

00:18:39.490 --> 00:18:42.140
we will plot the total
transmitted light

00:18:42.140 --> 00:18:43.645
as measured by that photodiode.

00:18:43.645 --> 00:18:46.890
And so I'm going to come up
with a hypothesis of what's

00:18:46.890 --> 00:18:47.844
going to happen.

00:18:47.844 --> 00:18:49.260
I'm going to say
that if we double

00:18:49.260 --> 00:18:51.870
