Cool.

00:22:06.690 --> 00:22:10.970
OK, so we notice that we have
some exponential character

00:22:10.970 --> 00:22:14.720
to be decay of the intensity
of the transmitted light

00:22:14.720 --> 00:22:16.220
through a medium.

00:22:16.220 --> 00:22:19.350
And the amount that's absorbed
is following another trend,

00:22:19.350 --> 00:22:21.054
which is just 1 minus that.

00:22:21.054 --> 00:22:22.470
So it's the amount
of light that's

00:22:22.470 --> 00:22:26.800
absorbed is following a curve
looks something like that.

00:22:26.800 --> 00:22:31.770
OK, so let's look through the
formalism of Beer-Lambert Law

00:22:31.770 --> 00:22:34.290
and try to understand
why it is that we come up

00:22:34.290 --> 00:22:37.310
with that exponential
function right here.

00:22:37.310 --> 00:22:42.290
So if we assume that light
is coming in a medium

00:22:42.290 --> 00:22:46.340
and light is decaying in
some function to that medium

00:22:46.340 --> 00:22:49.024
and a certain amount of
light is transmitted,

00:22:49.024 --> 00:22:50.940
we know, of course, from
our little experiment

00:22:50.940 --> 00:22:53.120
that it follows some
exponential function.

00:22:53.120 --> 00:22:55.157
But how do we justify
that to ourselves?

00:22:55.157 --> 00:22:57.240
Well, first off, we're
going to ignore reflections

00:22:57.240 --> 00:22:58.647
off the front surface.

00:22:58.647 --> 00:22:59.730
We just talked about them.

00:22:59.730 --> 00:23:01.070
We can calculate them.

00:23:01.070 --> 00:23:03.879
Let's leave that aside for
now as a parallel calculation.

00:23:03.879 --> 00:23:05.670
We're just concerning
ourselves with what's

00:23:05.670 --> 00:23:07.790
happening inside of the medium.

00:23:07.790 --> 00:23:10.390
So if we assume that
the change of intensity

00:23:10.390 --> 00:23:13.830
within that medium in each
little delta thickness

00:23:13.830 --> 00:23:18.010
is going to be affected by some
sort of scattering intensity

00:23:18.010 --> 00:23:21.930
within the medium--
and this sigma here

00:23:21.930 --> 00:23:24.020
can refer to a
variety of processes.

00:23:24.020 --> 00:23:26.750
That can refer to
absorption events

00:23:26.750 --> 00:23:29.770
that result in the
generation of free charge.

00:23:29.770 --> 00:23:32.290
They can refer to
absorption events that

00:23:32.290 --> 00:23:35.340
just heat the material up
and generate phonons, so

00:23:35.340 --> 00:23:36.800
lattice vibrations.

00:23:36.800 --> 00:23:39.920
There are a number of processes
embedded in the sigma,

00:23:39.920 --> 00:23:42.604
and that's why this formalism
is so powerful, because it

00:23:42.604 --> 00:23:45.020
doesn't care really what the
physical nature of that sigma

00:23:45.020 --> 00:23:45.640
is.

00:23:45.640 --> 00:23:50.140
It just matters that there is
an absorption per unit distance

00:23:50.140 --> 00:23:52.320
thickness traveled inside
of the material that

00:23:52.320 --> 00:23:54.930
is constant throughout
the entire material.

00:23:54.930 --> 00:23:58.750
So the sigma here is independent
of thickness throughout.

00:23:58.750 --> 00:24:00.680
And then as you integrate
through, you wind up

00:24:00.680 --> 00:24:04.440
with that beautiful exponential
function at the end,

00:24:04.440 --> 00:24:08.740
the sigma l times n.

00:24:08.740 --> 00:24:11.380
We collapse the n and the
sigma here into an alpha.

00:24:11.380 --> 00:24:13.950
That alpha is an
absorption coefficient.

00:24:13.950 --> 00:24:17.460
The l is the total length or the
total thickness of this medium

00:24:17.460 --> 00:24:18.430
right here.

00:24:18.430 --> 00:24:20.700
So if we increase
the total thickness,

00:24:20.700 --> 00:24:23.500
we're going to decrease
the total amount of light

00:24:23.500 --> 00:24:25.790
coming through via that
exponential function.

00:24:25.790 --> 00:24:28.380
The alpha, on the other hand,
is not a geometric parameter.

00:24:28.380 --> 00:24:31.240
It's an intrinsic
material parameter.

00:24:31.240 --> 00:24:33.379
To put that in terms of
mechanical engineering,

00:24:33.379 --> 00:24:35.420
for many of the mechanical
engineers in the room,

00:24:35.420 --> 00:24:38.400
you recall from solid
mechanics, 2001,

00:24:38.400 --> 00:24:41.370
that you have geometric
parameters that determine, say

00:24:41.370 --> 00:24:44.120
for example, structural
response and intrinsic material

00:24:44.120 --> 00:24:46.630
parameters like
Young's modulus that

00:24:46.630 --> 00:24:49.530
determine the structural
response of a system.

00:24:49.530 --> 00:24:51.930
And likewise in
here, in the optical,

00:24:51.930 --> 00:24:55.030
shall we say, response, we
have a fundamental intrinsic

00:24:55.030 --> 00:24:57.970
material parameter, r alpha,
the absorption coefficient,

00:24:57.970 --> 00:25:02.750
and the geometric parameter,
rl, which is the thickness.

00:25:02.750 --> 00:25:04.700
And the beauty of
this formalism right

00:25:04.700 --> 00:25:07.100
here is that we can
measure, experimentally

00:25:07.100 --> 00:25:10.300
just like we did right there,
our alphas for materials.

00:25:10.300 --> 00:25:12.220
And so from an
engineering point of view,

00:25:12.220 --> 00:25:15.100
we don't really--
to first order,

00:25:15.100 --> 00:25:17.582
it doesn't really matter
what sort of scattering

00:25:17.582 --> 00:25:19.290
or absorption process
is happening inside

00:25:19.290 --> 00:25:21.215
of a material for us
to calculate the amount

00:25:21.215 --> 00:25:22.090
of transmitted light.

00:25:22.090 --> 00:25:23.760
We just need to know the alpha.

00:25:23.760 --> 00:25:27.650
We need to know the optical
absorption coefficient.

00:25:27.650 --> 00:25:32.205
This alpha will vary as a
function of wavelength inside

00:25:32.205 --> 00:25:33.580
of a material
because, obviously,

00:25:33.580 --> 00:25:36.280
the physical absorption
mechanisms are varying

00:25:36.280 --> 00:25:37.480
as a function of wavelength.

00:25:37.480 --> 00:25:39.740
The resonances with
different electronic states

00:25:39.740 --> 00:25:41.642
within the material,
that light, depends

00:25:41.642 --> 00:25:43.850
on the energy of the light,
depends on the frequency.

00:25:43.850 --> 00:25:45.308
So there's a
wavelength dependence.

00:25:47.740 --> 00:25:52.190
Yeah, and that general
equation is the same one that

00:25:52.190 --> 00:25:56.010
drives the reduction
of light intensity

00:25:56.010 --> 00:25:57.600
as it travels through
the atmosphere.

00:25:57.600 --> 00:25:59.517
So if we increase the
atmospheric path length,

00:25:59.517 --> 00:26:01.975
we'll be reducing the amount
of light that actually reaches

00:26:01.975 --> 00:26:03.400
the surface of the earth.

00:26:03.400 --> 00:26:06.120
That's at air mass
two or air mass three,

00:26:06.120 --> 00:26:08.430
there's less solar
flux coming down

00:26:08.430 --> 00:26:11.231
than at air mass one
or air mass zero.

00:26:11.231 --> 00:26:12.730
The alpha, obviously,
is going to be

00:26:12.730 --> 00:26:14.110
very different
for our atmosphere

00:26:14.110 --> 00:26:17.196
than it was for these
little polyethylene sheets.

00:26:17.196 --> 00:26:19.320
Because the nature of the
scattering and absorption

00:26:19.320 --> 00:26:21.540
processes are very
different for the atmosphere

00:26:21.540 --> 00:26:25.750
than it is for here, the density
of the material and so forth.

00:26:25.750 --> 00:26:26.860
Any questions?

00:26:26.860 --> 00:26:27.514
Yes?

00:26:27.514 --> 00:26:29.170
AUDIENCE: What was n?

00:26:29.170 --> 00:26:33.680
TONIO BUONASSISI: So the n,
there's a certain scattering

00:26:33.680 --> 00:26:37.040
intensity, and then there's
a certain number density,

00:26:37.040 --> 00:26:38.800
for example, of the material.

00:26:38.800 --> 00:26:46.210
So this alpha here is, I
would say, density neutral.

00:26:46.210 --> 00:26:52.850
What we've done is we have
the alpha encapsulating

00:26:52.850 --> 00:26:54.820
the physical parameters
of the material

00:26:54.820 --> 00:26:58.860
and the absorption processes
all in one variable,

00:26:58.860 --> 00:27:01.080
very nicely and succinctly.

00:27:01.080 --> 00:27:03.740
And the only geometric
parameter that is of essence

00:27:03.740 --> 00:27:06.840
is really our l.

00:27:06.840 --> 00:27:08.840
AUDIENCE: It's called an
absorption coefficient,

00:27:08.840 --> 00:27:12.298
but is it more of an
extension coefficient, really?

00:27:12.298 --> 00:27:15.969
Because it's kind of confusing
that it includes scattering.

00:27:15.969 --> 00:27:18.260
TONIO BUONASSISI: The extension
coefficient, absorption

00:27:18.260 --> 00:27:23.750
coefficient, yes,
in solar research,

00:27:23.750 --> 00:27:25.820
when we talk about an
absorption coefficient

00:27:25.820 --> 00:27:27.570
inside of a material.

00:27:27.570 --> 00:27:31.390
Oftentimes we're operating in
a wavelength regime of light

00:27:31.390 --> 00:27:33.690
wherein free charge is excited.

00:27:33.690 --> 00:27:37.460
But we can also keep increasing
that the wavelength of light,

00:27:37.460 --> 00:27:40.480
say, out to 10 microns, very
long wavelength light, very

00:27:40.480 --> 00:27:41.800
low energy light.

00:27:41.800 --> 00:27:43.220
And that can excite
free carriers

00:27:43.220 --> 00:27:45.340
within the material--
carriers that

00:27:45.340 --> 00:27:47.590
are already excited, essentially
excited them further,

00:27:47.590 --> 00:27:49.080
without generating
any new free carriers

00:27:49.080 --> 00:27:49.850
inside of our material.

00:27:49.850 --> 00:27:51.010
So we won't necessarily
be generating

00:27:51.010 --> 00:27:52.730
more current by
shedding light on it

00:27:52.730 --> 00:27:56.470
but will be absorbing light,
nevertheless, in our material.

00:27:56.470 --> 00:27:58.980
So it's important
to keep, let's say,

00:27:58.980 --> 00:28:01.460
the underlying
physical processes that

00:28:01.460 --> 00:28:02.860
are occurring distinct.

00:28:02.860 --> 00:28:04.370
Later on we'll get to that.

00:28:04.370 --> 00:28:06.370
For now, it's important
just to, I would say,

00:28:06.370 --> 00:28:08.921
recognize that we have
an exponential decay

00:28:08.921 --> 00:28:11.420
of the intensity of the light
as it goes through the medium.

00:28:11.420 --> 00:28:12.830
And then over the
next few classes,

00:28:12.830 --> 00:28:14.790
we're going to get to exactly
what physical processes are

00:28:14.790 --> 00:28:15.570
going on.

00:28:15.570 --> 00:28:19.620
But I'm glad people are
asking those questions.

00:28:19.620 --> 00:28:21.914
OK, so again,
alpha is a function

00:28:21.914 --> 00:28:24.330
of the wavelength of light and
the property of the medium.

00:28:24.330 --> 00:28:27.060
And let me just
flash up some curves

00:28:27.060 --> 00:28:31.360
of alpha versus wavelength
so people have some exposure

00:28:31.360 --> 00:28:33.970
to those numbers.

00:28:33.970 --> 00:28:37.480
Again, we're talking about
an energy range quite broad

00:28:37.480 --> 00:28:41.800
here, from about
6.2 eV to 0.62 eV.

00:28:41.800 --> 00:28:43.700
The visible
wavelengths range would

00:28:43.700 --> 00:28:45.290
be somewhere in
this regime right

00:28:45.290 --> 00:28:47.360
here, so a very limited band.

00:28:47.360 --> 00:28:51.950
And the infrared out here,
ultraviolet over here,

00:28:51.950 --> 00:28:54.640
and we can see for a variety
of different types of materials

00:28:54.640 --> 00:28:57.310
what the absorption
coefficient is.

00:28:57.310 --> 00:29:00.060
So here we have germanium.

00:29:00.060 --> 00:29:03.690
The red would be crystalline
silicon, gallium arsenide,

00:29:03.690 --> 00:29:06.880
indium phosphide, and
amorphous silicon.

00:29:06.880 --> 00:29:08.960
So let's do a little
quick calculation

00:29:08.960 --> 00:29:10.400
just to get us a little limber.

00:29:10.400 --> 00:29:13.040
We're starting to get
into the semester,

00:29:13.040 --> 00:29:14.760
so the energy level
starts going down.

00:29:14.760 --> 00:29:17.700
What we're going to do is
we're going to pick a value,

00:29:17.700 --> 00:29:19.490
say 550 nanometers.

00:29:19.490 --> 00:29:21.350
Why did I pick 550 again?

00:29:21.350 --> 00:29:23.350
It's near the peak of the
