of light absorbed inside of it?

00:34:43.140 --> 00:34:45.000
AUDIENCE: Put anti-relfective
coating on it.

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:47.583
TONIO BUONASSISI: You could put
anti-reflective coating on it.

00:34:47.583 --> 00:34:49.125
Let's do something
much more simple.

00:34:49.125 --> 00:34:51.000
AUDIENCE: Put reflective
coating on the back.

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:51.909
TONIO BUONASSISI: Reflecting
coating on the back,

00:34:51.909 --> 00:34:52.520
absolutely.

00:34:52.520 --> 00:34:52.770
Yeah.

00:34:52.770 --> 00:34:55.228
So if the light goes through
the solar cell and doesn't get

00:34:55.228 --> 00:34:57.512
absorbed, that 10% of the
light that didn't make it,

00:34:57.512 --> 00:34:58.970
that's going to
get reflected back.

00:34:58.970 --> 00:35:00.934
It's going to get another
chance to go through.

00:35:00.934 --> 00:35:03.100
So if you absorb 90% of the
light on the first pass,

00:35:03.100 --> 00:35:05.760
you'll absorb 99% of the
light on two bounces, right?

00:35:05.760 --> 00:35:07.780
Or in one bounce,
rather, and two trips,

00:35:07.780 --> 00:35:10.120
two optical path links
through the material.

00:35:10.120 --> 00:35:12.290
And so the term
optical path length

00:35:12.290 --> 00:35:15.840
is a very important term
here, because the optical path

00:35:15.840 --> 00:35:18.530
length does not have to be
the thickness of the material.

00:35:18.530 --> 00:35:21.410
Ideally, the optical path
length through the material

00:35:21.410 --> 00:35:24.572
is much, much thicker than
the actual material itself.

00:35:24.572 --> 00:35:26.030
And over the next
few slides, we're

00:35:26.030 --> 00:35:29.550
going to learn how
we engineer that.

00:35:29.550 --> 00:35:34.420
So methods to improve optical
absorption- generally,

00:35:34.420 --> 00:35:37.230
these are called light trapping.

00:35:37.230 --> 00:35:40.860
Not all of these entail
trapping the light.

00:35:40.860 --> 00:35:42.570
Actually, most of them do.

00:35:42.570 --> 00:35:44.350
We also call them
light management

00:35:44.350 --> 00:35:47.080
as a more general
term that includes

00:35:47.080 --> 00:35:51.830
reflection and absorption
inside of the material.

00:35:51.830 --> 00:35:54.305
So the very simplest thing we
can do on the front surface--

00:35:54.305 --> 00:35:55.680
so what we're
going to do is take

00:35:55.680 --> 00:35:59.271
this step by step, as light
goes into the solar cell

00:35:59.271 --> 00:36:01.520
from the front side, we're
going to take step by step,

00:36:01.520 --> 00:36:04.050
what can we do to improve
the amount of light that

00:36:04.050 --> 00:36:05.150
is absorbed?

00:36:05.150 --> 00:36:08.114
The first thing that we can do
is texturize our front surface.

00:36:08.114 --> 00:36:10.030
If we don't have texture
on our front surface,

00:36:10.030 --> 00:36:12.240
if it's absolutely
flat, what we call

00:36:12.240 --> 00:36:17.110
specular surface-- specular
coming from the root mirror.

00:36:17.110 --> 00:36:20.880
In Latin languages, for example,
Italian specchio is mirror.

00:36:20.880 --> 00:36:24.800
So a flat silicon substrate,
a specular surface,

00:36:24.800 --> 00:36:27.344
would reflect some
finite amount of light.

00:36:27.344 --> 00:36:29.010
And we can calculate
that now because we

00:36:29.010 --> 00:36:31.090
know that it relates
to the real component

00:36:31.090 --> 00:36:33.380
of the refractive
index of the material.

00:36:33.380 --> 00:36:35.480
Now if we texturize
our surface--

00:36:35.480 --> 00:36:39.580
this is representing kind of
a pyramid type texturization.

00:36:39.580 --> 00:36:43.260
If the light comes in
and some fraction doesn't

00:36:43.260 --> 00:36:45.152
go into the material--
there's some component

00:36:45.152 --> 00:36:47.360
of that ray that's going
into the material over here,

00:36:47.360 --> 00:36:48.900
but we're ignoring
it in this drawing.

00:36:48.900 --> 00:36:50.316
We're just focusing
on the lights,

00:36:50.316 --> 00:36:52.450
the rays that get reflected.

00:36:52.450 --> 00:36:54.330
That beam that
gets reflected off,

00:36:54.330 --> 00:36:56.502
instead of just going
back out toward the sun,

00:36:56.502 --> 00:36:58.210
it's now going toward
the material again.

00:36:58.210 --> 00:37:01.020
So it has a second chance
of getting absorbed.

00:37:01.020 --> 00:37:03.630
So you just went--
for example, let's say

00:37:03.630 --> 00:37:05.790
if you have a 10%
reflectivity on the surface,

00:37:05.790 --> 00:37:07.775
you went from a 10%
reflectivity over here

00:37:07.775 --> 00:37:10.800
to a 1% reflectivity over here.

00:37:10.800 --> 00:37:13.840
Because now you have the total
amount of light that gets

00:37:13.840 --> 00:37:20.060
reflected is 1 minus 0.9 squared
as opposed to 1 minus 0.9

00:37:20.060 --> 00:37:21.071
to the 1.

00:37:21.071 --> 00:37:23.320
In this case right here, the
amount of light that gets

00:37:23.320 --> 00:37:26.620
reflected, assuming
its 10% reflective,

00:37:26.620 --> 00:37:30.977
would be 1 minus
0.9, so 10% of light.

00:37:30.977 --> 00:37:32.810
And over here, the
amount of light that gets

00:37:32.810 --> 00:37:37.540
reflected would be 1 minus
0.9 quantity squared, so 1%

00:37:37.540 --> 00:37:38.870
instead of 10%.

00:37:38.870 --> 00:37:41.460
So texturization
increases the probability

00:37:41.460 --> 00:37:43.470
that light will
enter the device.

00:37:43.470 --> 00:37:47.250
And what it also does-- this
is a secondary benefit--

00:37:47.250 --> 00:37:50.220
is it increases the path length,
the effective path length,

00:37:50.220 --> 00:37:51.676
of the incoming light.

00:37:51.676 --> 00:37:53.800
And the way to understand
that particular phenomena

00:37:53.800 --> 00:37:55.710
is called Snell's Law.

00:37:55.710 --> 00:37:58.985
Well, even in the absence
of Snell's Law-- no,

00:37:58.985 --> 00:37:59.610
let's go there.

00:37:59.610 --> 00:38:01.010
Let's go there.

00:38:01.010 --> 00:38:03.000
So we have a texturized
front surface.

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:04.400
What's happening?

00:38:04.400 --> 00:38:08.110
Well, as the material goes
from one medium to another,

00:38:08.110 --> 00:38:10.220
the refractive index changes.

00:38:10.220 --> 00:38:12.690
We discussed this right at
the beginning of lecture.

00:38:12.690 --> 00:38:17.272
So the way in which the
electromagnetic wave oscillates

00:38:17.272 --> 00:38:18.730
the electrons
instead of the system

00:38:18.730 --> 00:38:20.900
is changing from one
medium to another,

00:38:20.900 --> 00:38:23.990
let's say from air into the
solar cell device from air

00:38:23.990 --> 00:38:27.560
into our silicon, for
example, right here.

00:38:27.560 --> 00:38:30.630
Now, we can ascribe the
refractive indices to air

00:38:30.630 --> 00:38:32.830
and to our silicon like so.

00:38:32.830 --> 00:38:36.770
And the light path
will obey what

00:38:36.770 --> 00:38:39.240
is called Snell's Law,
which is the product

00:38:39.240 --> 00:38:42.400
of the refractive index and
sine of that angle, the angle

00:38:42.400 --> 00:38:44.670
relative to the surface normal.

00:38:44.670 --> 00:38:46.290
So a simple way to
think about this

00:38:46.290 --> 00:38:50.270
is when the light goes from a
low index of refraction medium

00:38:50.270 --> 00:38:54.080
to a high index of refraction
medium, light bends

00:38:54.080 --> 00:38:57.287
toward or away from the normal?

00:38:57.287 --> 00:38:58.870
So if I'm going from
air into silicon,

00:38:58.870 --> 00:39:00.940
light would bend toward
the normal, right?

00:39:00.940 --> 00:39:04.180
So here my theta 1 is going
to be greater than theta 2.

00:39:04.180 --> 00:39:07.480
My light has bent toward the
normal, if this is my silicon

00:39:07.480 --> 00:39:10.590
and this white stuff
over here is my air.

00:39:10.590 --> 00:39:12.050
So light came in.

00:39:12.050 --> 00:39:13.760
It encountered the surface.

00:39:13.760 --> 00:39:17.380
The theta 1 was defined
as the angle of the light

00:39:17.380 --> 00:39:18.750
relative to the surface normal.

00:39:18.750 --> 00:39:20.100
That was my theta 1.

00:39:20.100 --> 00:39:22.450
My theta 2 is going to
be given as the ratio

00:39:22.450 --> 00:39:23.720
of the refractive indices.

00:39:23.720 --> 00:39:26.140
And because the refractive
index of silicon

00:39:26.140 --> 00:39:29.110
is going to be greater
than that of air,

00:39:29.110 --> 00:39:30.930
light would bend
toward the normal.

00:39:30.930 --> 00:39:34.000
And so what I have on a
macroscopic view over here,

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:36.660
if this is my surface
texture, light was coming in,

00:39:36.660 --> 00:39:37.760
it's now bent.

00:39:37.760 --> 00:39:39.810
And so the effective
optical path length

00:39:39.810 --> 00:39:42.450
is now larger than the
thickness of my device.

00:39:42.450 --> 00:39:44.320
It's kind of cool.

00:39:44.320 --> 00:39:49.390
So there are two benefits to
texturizing your front surface.

00:39:49.390 --> 00:39:53.200
One is you have an additional
pass, additional bounce,

00:39:53.200 --> 00:39:55.290
an additional encounter
with the material.

00:39:55.290 --> 00:39:58.439
So that reflected light gets
another chance to go in.

00:39:58.439 --> 00:39:59.980
And the second
benefit is that you're

00:39:59.980 --> 00:40:01.410
able to increase
the optical path

00:40:01.410 --> 00:40:08.720
length by the delta in
refractive indices and the fact

00:40:08.720 --> 00:40:11.445
that the path of the
light will be Snell's Law.

00:40:11.445 --> 00:40:15.480
Now another really interesting
aside of Snell's Law

00:40:15.480 --> 00:40:19.970
is that if light is trying to
go from a high index medium

00:40:19.970 --> 00:40:22.090
to a low index medium,
and if it's coming in

00:40:22.090 --> 00:40:24.980
at a very oblique
angle like this,

00:40:24.980 --> 00:40:27.000
if you run through
Snell's Law, you

00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:28.250
don't get an angle coming out.

00:40:28.250 --> 00:40:29.850
It actually falls
along the surface

00:40:29.850 --> 00:40:32.730
or actually bounces back in most
often, depending on the angle.

00:40:32.730 --> 00:40:35.142
And you have what is called
total internal reflection,

00:40:35.142 --> 00:40:36.600
which is this case
right over here.

00:40:36.600 --> 00:40:39.400
That little bounce,
that friendly bounce,

00:40:39.400 --> 00:40:42.990
of the light that went in
bounced off the back side

00:40:42.990 --> 00:40:44.840
and then was reflected back in.

00:40:44.840 --> 00:40:47.060
That's a total internal
reflection event.

00:40:47.060 --> 00:40:49.780
And that happens
in solar modules.

00:40:49.780 --> 00:40:52.070
Right here, when light
comes in, bounces off

00:40:52.070 --> 00:40:54.080
of the white back
skin right here,

00:40:54.080 --> 00:40:56.790
and then gets scattered
off at an angle,

00:40:56.790 --> 00:40:58.710
it can have a total
internal reflection off

00:40:58.710 --> 00:41:00.520
of the front surface
glass and have

00:41:00.520 --> 00:41:03.960
a second chance of getting back
into the solar cells inside.

00:41:03.960 --> 00:41:07.100
So that's one of the reasons
why you see this white spacing,

00:41:07.100 --> 00:41:09.280
the white colored material,
in between the cells,

00:41:09.280 --> 00:41:11.642
is that the light gets
reflected off of there.

00:41:11.642 --> 00:41:13.600
It doesn't make it very
aesthetically pleasing.

00:41:13.600 --> 00:41:15.100
You might want it
to look all black.

00:41:15.100 --> 00:41:17.224
And if you do want it to
look all black, what would

00:41:17.224 --> 00:41:17.870
you do instead?

00:41:23.120 --> 00:41:25.830
Instead of changing the back
skin, what other component

00:41:25.830 --> 00:41:27.520
might you change?

00:41:27.520 --> 00:41:28.510
AUDIENCE: The front.

00:41:28.510 --> 00:41:29.150
TONIO BUONASSISI:
The front, right?

00:41:29.150 --> 00:41:32.010
You might change the nature
of the anti-reflection coating

00:41:32.010 --> 00:41:33.320
on the glass.

00:41:33.320 --> 00:41:36.160
We'll get anti-reflection
coatings in a minute.

00:41:36.160 --> 00:41:38.107
So even if the
panel looks black,

00:41:38.107 --> 00:41:39.940
there are some really
aesthetically pleasing

00:41:39.940 --> 00:41:42.023
solar panels out there
that look completely black.

00:41:42.023 --> 00:41:43.600
They may still have
white back skin,

00:41:43.600 --> 00:41:46.095
but the glass is just very
good at absorbing that light

00:41:46.095 --> 00:41:48.560
and preventing it from escaping.

00:41:48.560 --> 00:41:52.360
OK, so to engineer front and
back surface reflectances,

00:41:52.360 --> 00:41:54.090
you really have to
carefully select

00:41:54.090 --> 00:41:56.050
your refractive indices
and your materials

00:41:56.050 --> 00:41:57.980
if you put on either side.

00:41:57.980 --> 00:42:01.370
And it's very important--
extremely important.

00:42:01.370 --> 00:42:05.230
To make a long story short, the
record efficiency solar cell

00:42:05.230 --> 00:42:09.380
that was announced this past
year in gallium arsenide

00:42:09.380 --> 00:42:13.630
was achieved because of
good light management.

00:42:13.630 --> 00:42:18.620
And we'll explain how that came
about perhaps towards lectures,

00:42:18.620 --> 00:42:21.000
maybe lectures eight or nine.

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:23.400
So I'm going to play a
little game with you, which

00:42:23.400 --> 00:42:25.570
is to look at a swimming pool.

00:42:25.570 --> 00:42:27.550
This is a pool
filled with water,

00:42:27.550 --> 00:42:29.890
which is refractive index 1.3.

00:42:29.890 --> 00:42:30.990
Air is 1.

00:42:30.990 --> 00:42:33.010
And so that's the normal
view, what we have.

00:42:33.010 --> 00:42:35.580
Light bends toward
the normal, right?

00:42:35.580 --> 00:42:38.870
And so you're able to
look down inside the pool

00:42:38.870 --> 00:42:41.416
that stuff that is not
in your line of sight,

00:42:41.416 --> 00:42:42.790
not in your direct
line of sight.

00:42:42.790 --> 00:42:44.930
That's because when you
look down, the ray of light

00:42:44.930 --> 00:42:46.388
is traveling like
this and it bends

00:42:46.388 --> 00:42:49.740
toward the normal and
likewise symmetric.

00:42:49.740 --> 00:42:52.360
So you're seeing
material down there.

00:42:52.360 --> 00:42:56.310
What change of
property would give you

00:42:56.310 --> 00:42:57.530
these two images over here.

00:42:57.530 --> 00:42:58.820
Let me give you a hint.

00:42:58.820 --> 00:43:01.760
In one of those two images,
the refractive index

00:43:01.760 --> 00:43:04.680
of the medium inside
the pool is not 1.3.

00:43:04.680 --> 00:43:08.286
It's 0.9.

00:43:08.286 --> 00:43:09.760
It's 0.9.

00:43:09.760 --> 00:43:14.900
And in another one of these
two, the refractive index

00:43:14.900 --> 00:43:18.340
of the medium is actually
going to be negative.

00:43:18.340 --> 00:43:21.750
We'll call it a negative
refractive index material,

00:43:21.750 --> 00:43:23.550
a negative index material.

00:43:23.550 --> 00:43:25.892
So which of these two
do you think is which?

00:43:25.892 --> 00:43:27.350
Why don't you turn
to your neighbor

00:43:27.350 --> 00:43:29.910
quickly and chat about it
without peeking at your lecture

00:43:29.910 --> 00:43:30.410
notes.

00:43:45.010 --> 00:43:48.860
So let me walk through, as you
begin honing in on your answers

00:43:48.860 --> 00:43:49.640
here.

00:43:49.640 --> 00:43:52.370
Think about what would
happen to the reflectivity

00:43:52.370 --> 00:43:54.860
of that front
surface of the water

00:43:54.860 --> 00:43:59.130
and what would happen to the
angle that the light travels,

00:43:59.130 --> 00:44:02.340
or the angle of refraction
of bending, shall

00:44:02.340 --> 00:44:05.240
you say, as the light goes
from one medium to another.

00:44:05.240 --> 00:44:10.596
So if we go to a refractive
index material of minus 1.3,

00:44:10.596 --> 00:44:12.220
will we change the
reflectivity at all?

00:44:15.884 --> 00:44:20.990
It depends, but the
answers here are shown,

00:44:20.990 --> 00:44:22.472
for this particular system.

00:44:22.472 --> 00:44:24.180
It would require
sitting down and walking

00:44:24.180 --> 00:44:26.469
through the equations,
but in essence

00:44:26.469 --> 00:44:29.010
right here, with the pool filled
with the negative refractive

00:44:29.010 --> 00:44:32.690
index material, you're
really affecting

00:44:32.690 --> 00:44:36.100
the angle at which light
is coming out of the pool.

00:44:36.100 --> 00:44:39.680
Here you can see the corner
of the pool, which you

00:44:39.680 --> 00:44:41.090
shouldn't even be able to see.

00:44:41.090 --> 00:44:42.840
It's just that the
light traveled this way

00:44:42.840 --> 00:44:45.620
and then came back because it
was a negative refractive index

00:44:45.620 --> 00:44:46.370
material.

00:44:46.370 --> 00:44:48.532
Light actually did something
like this, zoop, zoop.

00:44:48.532 --> 00:44:49.740
AUDIENCE: What's in the pool?

00:44:49.740 --> 00:44:51.400
TONIO BUONASSISI: Oh,
that's just a corner.

00:44:51.400 --> 00:44:52.400
So what is in that pool?

00:44:52.400 --> 00:44:54.420
That is a computer
generated graphic.

00:44:54.420 --> 00:44:56.410
This is not a real pool.

00:44:56.410 --> 00:44:58.730
There exists negative
refractive index materials

00:44:58.730 --> 00:45:01.640
but not in that volume yet.

00:45:01.640 --> 00:45:07.690
These are relatively small
things and very much a study

00:45:07.690 --> 00:45:08.880
in fundamental science.

00:45:08.880 --> 00:45:12.760
So in this case
right here, we have

00:45:12.760 --> 00:45:17.220
less of an acute bending
of our angle of light.

00:45:17.220 --> 00:45:19.610
So we don't get to see quite
as many features right here

00:45:19.610 --> 00:45:20.660
toward the edge.

00:45:20.660 --> 00:45:24.130
And the reflectivity
has changed as a result

00:45:24.130 --> 00:45:29.252
of having drastically modified
our reflection condition.

00:45:29.252 --> 00:45:31.460
AUDIENCE: Why does the
reflectivity seem to have gone

00:45:31.460 --> 00:45:35.070
up and the index has gone down?

00:45:35.070 --> 00:45:37.420
TONIO BUONASSISI: In
that particular case?

00:45:37.420 --> 00:45:39.710
I think what they were getting
at-- this is coming off

00:45:39.710 --> 00:45:40.460
of an SPI website.

00:45:40.460 --> 00:45:42.460
I think what they were
getting at is mostly just

00:45:42.460 --> 00:45:44.020
a change in the reflectivity.

00:45:44.020 --> 00:45:48.110
So they were trying to emphasize
that you were modifying

00:45:48.110 --> 00:45:50.630
the reflection off the
surface in addition

00:45:50.630 --> 00:45:53.640
to the angle at which the
light was exiting the material.

00:45:53.640 --> 00:45:58.580
I'm going to come back to
Snell's Law in a minute.

00:45:58.580 --> 00:46:02.060
But for the time being,
I want to move on

00:46:02.060 --> 00:46:05.450
to the next concept here,
which is Lambertian reflector.

00:46:05.450 --> 00:46:09.210
You'll hear this topic or this
word thrown around quite a lot

00:46:09.210 --> 00:46:10.770
in the solar cell community.

00:46:10.770 --> 00:46:13.760
And it's used rather liberally
to mean a lot of things.

00:46:13.760 --> 00:46:17.890
Although in optics, it has
a very specific meaning.

00:46:17.890 --> 00:46:20.410
So I'm going to show you
that very specific meaning

00:46:20.410 --> 00:46:24.100
and then describe for you
what it has very loosely come

00:46:24.100 --> 00:46:25.620
to mean in the solar industry.

00:46:25.620 --> 00:46:28.440
So a diffuse
Lambertian reflector

00:46:28.440 --> 00:46:32.610
will follow a reflectance
that follows a cosine theta

00:46:32.610 --> 00:46:33.920
dependence.

00:46:33.920 --> 00:46:36.530
So if you have light
coming into a sample,

00:46:36.530 --> 00:46:39.330
the surface normal, and
the outgoing light ray

00:46:39.330 --> 00:46:41.410
form an angle theta.

00:46:41.410 --> 00:46:43.240
And if the two are
perfectly aligned,

00:46:43.240 --> 00:46:45.390
you get a lot of reflectance
off of that angle.

00:46:45.390 --> 00:46:47.500
If the two are perpendicular
to one another,

00:46:47.500 --> 00:46:49.830
you get zero reflectance
in that angle.

00:46:49.830 --> 00:46:53.130
And so the reflectance parallel
to the surface here is zero.

00:46:53.130 --> 00:46:55.720
In everywhere in between,
the magnitude of reflectance

00:46:55.720 --> 00:46:57.480
is varying as consine theta.

00:46:57.480 --> 00:47:01.730
That's the, I would
say, pedantic definition

00:47:01.730 --> 00:47:03.550
of an Lambertian reflector.

00:47:03.550 --> 00:47:04.990
Often in the solar
industry you'll

00:47:04.990 --> 00:47:07.960
hear people, probably because
of a lack of optics background,

00:47:07.960 --> 00:47:10.470
just call any randomly
reflecting surface

00:47:10.470 --> 00:47:12.220
a Lambertian scatter.

00:47:12.220 --> 00:47:15.400
It's a very loosely used term.

00:47:15.400 --> 00:47:18.990
And it is wrong by the
book, but nevertheless, it's

00:47:18.990 --> 00:47:22.930
one of these things that
live on in our industry.

00:47:22.930 --> 00:47:26.190
So the difference between
a specular reflector,

00:47:26.190 --> 00:47:28.470
the one that we've just
been analyzing right now,

00:47:28.470 --> 00:47:30.880
and a Lambertian reflector,
is that typically the way

00:47:30.880 --> 00:47:35.490
these are made is that you
do have a random texture

00:47:35.490 --> 00:47:36.380
on your surface.

00:47:36.380 --> 00:47:38.921
And that's probably where the
origin of this misunderstanding

00:47:38.921 --> 00:47:39.900
comes about.

00:47:39.900 --> 00:47:42.445
We don't get a
random reflectance

00:47:42.445 --> 00:47:44.730
of the light coming off,
but the surface itself

00:47:44.730 --> 00:47:46.440
can be rather texturized.

00:47:46.440 --> 00:47:49.420
So, for example, if you suspect
that this little material

00:47:49.420 --> 00:47:52.110
right here might behave
like a Lambertian scatter,

00:47:52.110 --> 00:47:56.332
you might put it inside of
a tool and rotate the angle

00:47:56.332 --> 00:47:58.040
and measure the amount
of reflected light

00:47:58.040 --> 00:48:00.680
as a function of the angle
to determine whether or not

00:48:00.680 --> 00:48:03.510
it follows this cosine
theta dependence.

00:48:03.510 --> 00:48:07.510
And the reason it's important
is because the back skins

00:48:07.510 --> 00:48:11.619
of our solar modules can quite
often be Lambertian scatters.

00:48:11.619 --> 00:48:13.160
And we have a certain
amount of light

00:48:13.160 --> 00:48:15.140
that comes off at
some angle here

00:48:15.140 --> 00:48:17.760
that will get trapped by a
total internal reflection

00:48:17.760 --> 00:48:19.250
inside of a modules.

00:48:19.250 --> 00:48:23.790
So if, instead of having
macroscopic pyramids right

00:48:23.790 --> 00:48:26.780
here, you had very, very
small pyramids-- still not

00:48:26.780 --> 00:48:29.370
sub-wavelength, but
smaller features,

00:48:29.370 --> 00:48:32.340
for example, the texturization
on the back skin right here.

00:48:32.340 --> 00:48:34.260
An it managed to
scatter the light

00:48:34.260 --> 00:48:35.920
at a particular
angle that got caught

00:48:35.920 --> 00:48:37.380
by total internal reflection.

00:48:37.380 --> 00:48:39.900
Macroscopically, we might be
able to describe the scattering

00:48:39.900 --> 00:48:42.800
behavior of that surface
as Lambertian scatter.

00:48:42.800 --> 00:48:45.950
But it's those waves, those
rays that are bouncing off

00:48:45.950 --> 00:48:48.260
at those large angles
that are causing

00:48:48.260 --> 00:48:52.390
the total internal
reflection event.

00:48:52.390 --> 00:48:55.595
And so the notion of
a Lambertian scatter

00:48:55.595 --> 00:48:58.660
is important on the backsides
of solar cell devices.

00:48:58.660 --> 00:49:04.410
We would obviously wants to even
change the scattering profile.

00:49:04.410 --> 00:49:07.482
We wouldn't want necessarily
specular reflectance.

00:49:07.482 --> 00:49:09.940
We might want to maximize the
amount of light reflected off

00:49:09.940 --> 00:49:12.170
at particular angles.

00:49:12.170 --> 00:49:14.320
And there is, of
course, research

00:49:14.320 --> 00:49:18.050
being done to figure out
how to make light do that.

00:49:18.050 --> 00:49:20.790
I'll show you one example
at the very end of lecture,

00:49:20.790 --> 00:49:23.670
a paper that was just
published in Science last week,

00:49:23.670 --> 00:49:25.380
as an example.

00:49:25.380 --> 00:49:27.380
And so these
scattering centers off

00:49:27.380 --> 00:49:29.315
the backs of the
rear sides of cells

00:49:29.315 --> 00:49:31.440
would operate more or less
in the following manner.

00:49:31.440 --> 00:49:32.980
You'd have incoming light.

00:49:32.980 --> 00:49:35.360
Let's ignore front
surface texturing for now.

00:49:35.360 --> 00:49:36.980
Let's just focus
on the backside.

00:49:36.980 --> 00:49:39.770
And if you have some random, as
we call it, a random reflector,

00:49:39.770 --> 00:49:43.135
a randomly texturized reflector
on the back that reflects off

00:49:43.135 --> 00:49:45.860
in, say, a Lambertian
fashion, you'll

00:49:45.860 --> 00:49:48.430
have some fraction of
that light scattered off

00:49:48.430 --> 00:49:53.170
at an angle that is large
enough relative to the surface

00:49:53.170 --> 00:49:57.740
normal that it is trapped by
total internal reflection.

00:49:57.740 --> 00:50:01.090
And you don't only have
to texture your back skin.

00:50:01.090 --> 00:50:03.034
You can also texture
the bus bars.

00:50:03.034 --> 00:50:05.200
The bus bars are these
little metal wires right here

00:50:05.200 --> 00:50:07.709
that are collecting the charge
from each of the solar cells.

00:50:07.709 --> 00:50:09.750
And they're connecting
essentially the front side

00:50:09.750 --> 00:50:11.580
of one cell to the
backside of the next.

00:50:11.580 --> 00:50:13.000
If you want to think about it
as the cathode to the anode,

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:14.791
cathode to the anode,
cathode to the anode,

00:50:14.791 --> 00:50:17.130
stringing all these
cells together in series.

00:50:17.130 --> 00:50:19.110
And this metal right here
is just really shiny,

00:50:19.110 --> 00:50:22.070
and it's reflecting light
right back out into space.

00:50:22.070 --> 00:50:25.330
What if we instead were to
texture that metal so that when

00:50:25.330 --> 00:50:27.320
laser light shined on it
a certain amount would

00:50:27.320 --> 00:50:29.250
be reflected off at an
angle and then caught

00:50:29.250 --> 00:50:30.290
by total internal reflection.

00:50:30.290 --> 00:50:32.331
And that's exactly what
you're seeing right here.

00:50:32.331 --> 00:50:34.400
The light bounced here
on a textured bus bar,

00:50:34.400 --> 00:50:36.560
bounced off of the glass
more or less around here

00:50:36.560 --> 00:50:38.710
halfway, and then
got a second chance

00:50:38.710 --> 00:50:40.297
to enter the cell over here.

00:50:40.297 --> 00:50:41.880
Obviously some of
it is reflecting off

00:50:41.880 --> 00:50:43.090
so we can see it.

00:50:43.090 --> 00:50:44.480
But a lot of it's going in.

00:50:44.480 --> 00:50:46.492
And that little
innovation right there,

00:50:46.492 --> 00:50:47.950
which was developed
in the building

00:50:47.950 --> 00:50:50.470
right next door by
Professor Ely Sachs,

00:50:50.470 --> 00:50:53.290
can gain module performances
somewhere on the order

00:50:53.290 --> 00:50:55.430
of a few percent relative.

00:50:55.430 --> 00:50:57.430
So that might not
sound like a whole lot,

00:50:57.430 --> 00:51:01.930
but if you're a $100 billion
industry, 1% is a lot of money.

00:51:01.930 --> 00:51:05.040
So it does add up.

00:51:05.040 --> 00:51:08.410
So that goes back to the
total internal reflection.

00:51:08.410 --> 00:51:14.620
So there is a limit to
all of this texturization.

00:51:14.620 --> 00:51:18.350
There's a limit to how much
we can trap light simply

00:51:18.350 --> 00:51:23.930
by modifying or
corrugating the surfaces

00:51:23.930 --> 00:51:27.060
to enhance the optical path
length with these types

00:51:27.060 --> 00:51:32.220
of bounces using Snell's
Law and of course

00:51:32.220 --> 00:51:33.870
the general
reflectivity equations.

00:51:33.870 --> 00:51:37.470
And a gentleman by the name
of Eli Yablonovitch, who's

00:51:37.470 --> 00:51:40.690
now a professor in Berkeley
calculated these parameters

00:51:40.690 --> 00:51:45.130
I think back in 1982 and
came up with an upper limit

00:51:45.130 --> 00:51:46.740
to the optical path length.

00:51:46.740 --> 00:51:50.460
He, after a long
series of calculations,

00:51:50.460 --> 00:51:53.990
derived an expression
for the maximum increase

00:51:53.990 --> 00:51:56.710
of the optical path length
due to surface texturing,

00:51:56.710 --> 00:51:59.080
which was 4n squared.

00:51:59.080 --> 00:52:01.640
And the Yablonovitch
limit to this day

00:52:01.640 --> 00:52:05.870
is a pretty good litmus
test for the ability

00:52:05.870 --> 00:52:07.250
of a material to trap light.

00:52:07.250 --> 00:52:09.430
So if you have
silicon, for instance,

00:52:09.430 --> 00:52:12.030
with a refractive
index of, let's say,

00:52:12.030 --> 00:52:15.690
in the infrared some around
3.6, your Yablonovitch limit

00:52:15.690 --> 00:52:18.530
is around 50, which means
that you can increase

00:52:18.530 --> 00:52:20.860
the optical path
length by a factor 50,

00:52:20.860 --> 00:52:24.570
relative to the thickness
of your material.

00:52:24.570 --> 00:52:26.180
If you have an organic
material, which

00:52:26.180 --> 00:52:29.800
has a refractive index typically
of around maximum 2, then

00:52:29.800 --> 00:52:32.460
that would be squared, 16,
somewhere in that range.

00:52:32.460 --> 00:52:35.264
You can increase probably
in the order of 20

00:52:35.264 --> 00:52:37.180
the optical path length
inside of the material

00:52:37.180 --> 00:52:38.930
through texturization.

00:52:38.930 --> 00:52:42.180
So this is a useful
parameter for those

00:52:42.180 --> 00:52:43.890
who are doing research
in photovoltaics,

00:52:43.890 --> 00:52:45.480
the graduate
students especially.

00:52:45.480 --> 00:52:47.590
And so I think the
graduate students

00:52:47.590 --> 00:52:49.840
will have a question at some
point on the Yablonovitch

00:52:49.840 --> 00:52:51.610
limit.

00:52:51.610 --> 00:52:55.480
And so that's a useful
parameter to keep in your mind.

00:52:55.480 --> 00:53:00.320
Let me touch upon a few other
forms of trapping light.

00:53:00.320 --> 00:53:02.970
We've so far just
assumed that light

00:53:02.970 --> 00:53:07.340
behaves like a
continuous wave, doesn't

00:53:07.340 --> 00:53:09.900
interfere with anything,
doesn't interfere with itself.

00:53:09.900 --> 00:53:14.907
Now we're going to discuss some
anti-reflection effects which

00:53:14.907 --> 00:53:16.740
derives from the notion
that light is a wave

00:53:16.740 --> 00:53:20.470
and can constructively and
destructively interfere.

00:53:20.470 --> 00:53:25.300
What we have right here is
a layer of another material

00:53:25.300 --> 00:53:27.820
with a refractive
index, say n1, which

00:53:27.820 --> 00:53:30.070
is in between our
n0 which is at air

00:53:30.070 --> 00:53:31.800
and our n2 is the
absorber material,

00:53:31.800 --> 00:53:33.580
let's say the silicon.

00:53:33.580 --> 00:53:35.357
So we have a grading
of refractive indices

00:53:35.357 --> 00:53:37.190
going from air, our
anti-reflection coating,

00:53:37.190 --> 00:53:38.270
to silicon.

00:53:38.270 --> 00:53:40.895
And right over here we have
a certain thickness, d1.

00:53:40.895 --> 00:53:43.890
And over here we have a
certain thickness, d2.

00:53:43.890 --> 00:53:47.760
So what is happening
in these two images?

00:53:47.760 --> 00:53:51.540
Let me show you with another,
a little bit more clear figure,

00:53:51.540 --> 00:53:53.680
coming from our
beloved Wikipedia,

00:53:53.680 --> 00:53:56.140
and then go back to that
other image right there.

00:53:56.140 --> 00:53:59.710
So what's happening is we
have an incoming wave that

00:53:59.710 --> 00:54:02.110
for some reason is
ignoring Snell's Law.

00:54:02.110 --> 00:54:02.949
It's beyond me.

00:54:02.949 --> 00:54:04.990
But anyway, the wave is
going in a straight line.

00:54:04.990 --> 00:54:07.470
It should be bending toward
the surface norm, obviously.

00:54:07.470 --> 00:54:11.290
But we have reflections
off of this interface

00:54:11.290 --> 00:54:14.190
and this interface right here.

00:54:14.190 --> 00:54:19.530
And because the
thickness of this layer

00:54:19.530 --> 00:54:22.360
is in the order
of lambda over 4,

00:54:22.360 --> 00:54:24.090
that means that the
wave that's going in

00:54:24.090 --> 00:54:26.131
will be phase shifted
relative to the wave that's

00:54:26.131 --> 00:54:28.650
reflected off the front surface,
first by lambda over 4 then

00:54:28.650 --> 00:54:30.610
2 times lambda over
4, in other words,

00:54:30.610 --> 00:54:33.530
lambda over 2, which means that
the two waves are out of phase

00:54:33.530 --> 00:54:36.510
by lambda over 2, which means
that they will destructively

00:54:36.510 --> 00:54:38.512
interfere.

00:54:38.512 --> 00:54:39.720
The peak will be at a trough.

00:54:39.720 --> 00:54:41.695
The trough will be at a peak.

00:54:41.695 --> 00:54:44.320
So the two waves will are going
to be destructively interfering

00:54:44.320 --> 00:54:45.180
when they come out.

00:54:45.180 --> 00:54:47.096
If you add these two
together, due to the wave

00:54:47.096 --> 00:54:51.170
nature of light, you get
suppressed reflectance.

00:54:51.170 --> 00:54:53.800
And that's a really
interesting property.

00:54:53.800 --> 00:54:56.630
You can begin varying the
thickness of this layer,

00:54:56.630 --> 00:54:59.270
and of course changing the
nature of the reflected light.

00:54:59.270 --> 00:55:01.735
You can constructively
interfere if you like

00:55:01.735 --> 00:55:04.440
and enhance the amount
of reflected light

00:55:04.440 --> 00:55:07.770
as a result of this
interference effect.

00:55:07.770 --> 00:55:11.050
Obviously, in most solar cells,
we want to suppress reflection.

00:55:11.050 --> 00:55:12.800
And so we go to great
lengths to make sure

00:55:12.800 --> 00:55:16.200
that this thickness as well
as the refractive index

00:55:16.200 --> 00:55:23.880
of the material is optimized
for a particular system.

00:55:23.880 --> 00:55:29.020
And so without going
into the hairy math,

00:55:29.020 --> 00:55:33.494
to calculate this right here,
it's definitely possible.

00:55:33.494 --> 00:55:35.410
It's definitely something
that should be done.

00:55:35.410 --> 00:55:37.618
And I believe the graduate
students have it assigned.

00:55:37.618 --> 00:55:39.490
It's the very last
problem in the homework.

00:55:39.490 --> 00:55:43.690
But for a very simple kind of
conceptual understanding that

00:55:43.690 --> 00:55:45.860
is wavelength
independent, if we want

00:55:45.860 --> 00:55:50.030
to minimize the reflectance at
a particular wavelength, let's

00:55:50.030 --> 00:55:53.570
call it at a lambda
0, which is the photon

00:55:53.570 --> 00:55:56.700
wavelength at the peak
of the solar spectrum,

00:55:56.700 --> 00:55:59.549
we have to design the thickness
of our anti-reflection coating

00:55:59.549 --> 00:56:01.090
to satisfy that
equation right there,

00:56:01.090 --> 00:56:02.640
essentially lambda over 4.

00:56:02.640 --> 00:56:04.772
That's the phase
shift we want upon one

00:56:04.772 --> 00:56:06.230
pass of the
anti-reflection coating

00:56:06.230 --> 00:56:08.000
so that two passes,
when it goes through

00:56:08.000 --> 00:56:09.440
and then back,
it's phase shifted

00:56:09.440 --> 00:56:11.630
relative to the surface
reflected light by lambda

00:56:11.630 --> 00:56:15.390
over 2, divided by n, n
being the refractive index

00:56:15.390 --> 00:56:16.830
of the material.

00:56:16.830 --> 00:56:20.234
Obviously the frequency of
light is staying the same

00:56:20.234 --> 00:56:21.900
as it goes from one
material to another.

00:56:21.900 --> 00:56:25.040
But the wavelength
would be changing.

00:56:25.040 --> 00:56:28.250
So that's why the n
parameter appears right here

00:56:28.250 --> 00:56:29.580
in this equation.

00:56:29.580 --> 00:56:32.350
The t is the thickness of the
optimal anti-reflection coating

00:56:32.350 --> 00:56:33.470
thickness.

00:56:33.470 --> 00:56:38.425
So just to give us a
sense, kind of an estimate,

00:56:38.425 --> 00:56:40.550
and to give us some confidence
in these engineering

00:56:40.550 --> 00:56:42.720
methods, what I'd
like you to do is

00:56:42.720 --> 00:56:47.390
to calculate the thickness of an
ideal anti-reflective coating.

00:56:47.390 --> 00:56:49.730
This anti-reflective coating
right here on these cells--

00:56:49.730 --> 00:56:51.855
I apologize, they also have
the metal on the front,

00:56:51.855 --> 00:56:54.280
so it's a little difficult to
distinguish between the two.

00:56:54.280 --> 00:56:58.260
But in my right hand, this one,
I have a piece of bare silicon.

00:56:58.260 --> 00:57:00.610
And you can see it's
rather reflective.

00:57:00.610 --> 00:57:03.180
In my left hand
over here, I have

00:57:03.180 --> 00:57:05.690
a piece of silicon with
an anti-reflective coating

00:57:05.690 --> 00:57:08.146
as well some contact
metalization on the front.

00:57:08.146 --> 00:57:09.770
So that's why you
see those grid lines.

00:57:09.770 --> 00:57:11.700
But it looks very blue.

00:57:11.700 --> 00:57:13.497
It looks very blue
because the cell

00:57:13.497 --> 00:57:15.830
is absorbing very well at the
peak of the solar spectrum

00:57:15.830 --> 00:57:18.180
which is in the yellow.

00:57:18.180 --> 00:57:23.320
So calculate for me what
is the optimal thickness

00:57:23.320 --> 00:57:26.110
of an anti-reflection
coating of silicon nitride?

00:57:26.110 --> 00:57:29.010
And we'll give it a
refractive index of, say, 2.1.

00:57:29.010 --> 00:57:31.360
Let me see if those
numbers make sense,

00:57:31.360 --> 00:57:35.640
so refractive index of silicon
nitride somewhere around 550.

00:57:35.640 --> 00:57:38.160
Let's call it 2, just
make our lives simple.

00:57:38.160 --> 00:57:41.730
And the peak of the solar
spectrum we'll again call 550.

00:57:41.730 --> 00:57:43.584
So why don't we run
the numbers quickly.

00:57:43.584 --> 00:57:44.834
What should that thickness be?

00:57:54.983 --> 00:57:56.524
AUDIENCE: Tonio,
I'm sorry, could you

00:57:56.524 --> 00:57:57.852
repeat the constant again?

00:57:57.852 --> 00:57:58.810
TONIO BUONASSISI: Sure.

00:57:58.810 --> 00:58:03.210
So the n, the refractive
index, is going to be around 2

00:58:03.210 --> 00:58:04.690
for silicon nitride.

00:58:04.690 --> 00:58:07.400
So we're going from air, which
is around refractive index one,

00:58:07.400 --> 00:58:10.810
to silicon nitride, the silicon.

00:58:10.810 --> 00:58:14.500
And the peak of the solar
spectrum, our lambda 0,

00:58:14.500 --> 00:58:16.530
which is the photon
wavelength at the peak

00:58:16.530 --> 00:58:20.740
of the solar spectrum in vacuum
or in air, is 550 nanometers.

00:58:26.950 --> 00:58:29.760
So what thicknesses are
folks coming up with?

00:58:29.760 --> 00:58:31.200
Order of magnitude.

00:58:31.200 --> 00:58:32.200
AUDIENCE: 70 nanometers.

00:58:32.200 --> 00:58:33.533
TONIO BUONASSISI: 70 nanometers.

00:58:33.533 --> 00:58:37.420
That's almost spot on
to the actual thickness,

00:58:37.420 --> 00:58:39.670
to somewhere on the
order between 70 to 80

00:58:39.670 --> 00:58:42.380
nanometer typically.

00:58:42.380 --> 00:58:46.210
You're telling me that
something that is 1/1,000,

00:58:46.210 --> 00:58:49.540
the thickness of my hair,
is deposited on the surface

00:58:49.540 --> 00:58:53.060
of this wafer and is
absorbing all this light?

00:58:53.060 --> 00:58:54.256
That's pretty cool.

00:58:54.256 --> 00:58:55.630
And it's not
absorbing the light.

00:58:55.630 --> 00:58:56.870
The anti-reflective
coating is not

00:58:56.870 --> 00:58:58.280
absorbing the light,
which is really important.

00:58:58.280 --> 00:58:59.779
We want the solar
cell underneath it

00:58:59.779 --> 00:59:00.890
to be absorbing the light.

00:59:00.890 --> 00:59:03.440
The anti-reflection coding
is enabling the light

00:59:03.440 --> 00:59:07.790
to be absorbed because it's
suppressing the reflectance.

00:59:07.790 --> 00:59:10.120
The reflected modes at
that particular wavelength

00:59:10.120 --> 00:59:13.900
are suppressed because of
the destructive interference.

00:59:13.900 --> 00:59:15.410
That's cool.

00:59:15.410 --> 00:59:18.530
I really get a kick out of
anti-reflective coatings.

00:59:18.530 --> 00:59:22.070
So they're 70 nanometers thick.

00:59:22.070 --> 00:59:24.780
And you gain quite a lot in
terms of cell performance.

00:59:27.560 --> 00:59:30.850
I'll show you some slides to
drive that point home in a bit.

00:59:34.600 --> 00:59:37.600
This is really really briefly--
I'll post these slides online

00:59:37.600 --> 00:59:39.320
so you can have access to them.

00:59:39.320 --> 00:59:42.560
If you use the matrix
transfer method,

00:59:42.560 --> 00:59:46.880
as described beautifully in
[? Gonchen's ?] textbook,

00:59:46.880 --> 00:59:50.280
you can calculate the
amount of light reflected

00:59:50.280 --> 00:59:54.360
across a broad spectral
range for a given thickness

00:59:54.360 --> 00:59:55.600
of anti-reflection coding.

00:59:55.600 --> 00:59:57.500
So what we did right
now was to calculate

00:59:57.500 --> 01:00:00.370
a suppression of the light
at a particular wavelength.

01:00:00.370 --> 01:00:02.920
But you can also calculate
with the tools that

01:00:02.920 --> 01:00:06.890
are available to
you the reflectance

01:00:06.890 --> 01:00:09.140
of your particular device
over a broader wavelength.

01:00:09.140 --> 01:00:11.090
Range and that's pretty
cool because now you

01:00:11.090 --> 01:00:14.520
can begin, say, multiplying
this function right

01:00:14.520 --> 01:00:17.540
here against your solar
spectrum and begin

01:00:17.540 --> 01:00:21.000
to calculate the total amount
of light entering your sample

01:00:21.000 --> 01:00:22.960
and the total energy
entering your sample.

01:00:22.960 --> 01:00:25.420
Equations, brilliant.

01:00:25.420 --> 01:00:27.730
The important thing
to note here is

01:00:27.730 --> 01:00:30.550
that it really, really matters.

01:00:30.550 --> 01:00:32.970
This is silicon under
glass right here,

01:00:32.970 --> 01:00:35.730
for example, typical solar
cell material in blue.

01:00:35.730 --> 01:00:37.320
It's better than
the bare silicon.

01:00:37.320 --> 01:00:40.550
Why is it better than the bare
silicon, silicon under glass?

01:00:40.550 --> 01:00:42.500
Glass has a refractive
index of 1.5 or so.

01:00:45.886 --> 01:00:48.316
AUDIENCE: The index matching.

01:00:48.316 --> 01:00:52.690
You go from pairs 1 to 2.3
and then to [INAUDIBLE].

01:00:52.690 --> 01:00:56.277
The difference is small
between the classes.

01:00:56.277 --> 01:00:57.360
TONIO BUONASSISI: Exactly.

01:00:57.360 --> 01:00:58.900
So if we recall
that equation that

01:00:58.900 --> 01:01:00.400
described the amount
of reflectance,

01:01:00.400 --> 01:01:04.260
there was that-- what was it--
n1 minus n2 quantity squared,

01:01:04.260 --> 01:01:04.760
right?

01:01:04.760 --> 01:01:07.210
So the bigger the delta
between the ends, the bigger

01:01:07.210 --> 01:01:08.710
the difference in
refractive indices

01:01:08.710 --> 01:01:10.330
between material one
and material two,

01:01:10.330 --> 01:01:12.890
the more the reflectance is
going to be off that interface.

01:01:12.890 --> 01:01:15.460
And so you can begin
reducing reflectance off

01:01:15.460 --> 01:01:18.530
of a stack of light
going both ways

01:01:18.530 --> 01:01:22.730
by grading the refractive
index of the material.

01:01:22.730 --> 01:01:26.380
And that, of course, changes the
reflectance in both directions.

01:01:26.380 --> 01:01:29.489
And so you get a reduction
in the total amount

01:01:29.489 --> 01:01:31.780
of reflected light when you
put the silicon under glass

01:01:31.780 --> 01:01:35.620
because glass has a refractive
index somewhere between air

01:01:35.620 --> 01:01:37.750
and silicon.

01:01:37.750 --> 01:01:39.480
And then you get a
further reduction

01:01:39.480 --> 01:01:43.370
of the reflectance when you
have an anti-reflection coating

01:01:43.370 --> 01:01:45.730
with a refractive index
somewhere around--

01:01:45.730 --> 01:01:47.830
for this particular
system, silicon again

01:01:47.830 --> 01:01:49.570
has a higher refractive index.

01:01:49.570 --> 01:01:52.300
This used in anti-reflective
coating of a refractive index

01:01:52.300 --> 01:01:56.710
of 2.3 of some
thickness, probably

01:01:56.710 --> 01:01:59.800
somewhere around--
let's see, it'd

01:01:59.800 --> 01:02:03.520
be greater or smaller,
probably around 65,

01:02:03.520 --> 01:02:05.610
75 nanometer
somewhere that range.

01:02:05.610 --> 01:02:08.630
So what this is
saying is that you

01:02:08.630 --> 01:02:11.350
can minimize the
reflection of light

01:02:11.350 --> 01:02:13.080
off of the front
surface of your sample

01:02:13.080 --> 01:02:15.990
by using an intelligent
combination of the very

01:02:15.990 --> 01:02:18.040
first equation that we're
exposed to in the class

01:02:18.040 --> 01:02:20.480
today, which was the
reflected light as a function

01:02:20.480 --> 01:02:22.646
of refractive index, so
essentially refractive index

01:02:22.646 --> 01:02:25.490
matching and secondly, by
engineering by engineering

01:02:25.490 --> 01:02:28.220
an anti-reflective
coating, which oftentimes

01:02:28.220 --> 01:02:29.690
in the lingo of
solar cell science

01:02:29.690 --> 01:02:32.540
we call it an ARC, an
anti-reflective coating.

01:02:32.540 --> 01:02:36.430
And those two things combined
give us very low reflection

01:02:36.430 --> 01:02:39.190
off of the front surface.

01:02:39.190 --> 01:02:47.000
Probably 5% of our R&D
cells that we make at MIT

01:02:47.000 --> 01:02:49.640
use these sorts of
technologies, which are pretty

01:02:49.640 --> 01:02:51.210
standard in the industry.

01:02:51.210 --> 01:02:54.650
And you can see what
the hit is, right?

01:02:54.650 --> 01:02:56.610
Let's see, if I'm just
using a bare material,

01:02:56.610 --> 01:02:58.770
if I'm getting 30%
reflection, I'm

01:02:58.770 --> 01:03:04.010
getting a 30% drop in the
current output of my device.

01:03:04.010 --> 01:03:05.680
That's pretty significant.

01:03:05.680 --> 01:03:08.560
So these are simple ways to
improve performance of devices.

01:03:11.430 --> 01:03:15.160
If you want to become
fancy and actually do

01:03:15.160 --> 01:03:19.080
what's called a ray tracing
to calculate the path of light

01:03:19.080 --> 01:03:22.110
through a medium, there
is software available

01:03:22.110 --> 01:03:24.950
that will take all of
what we've discussed today

01:03:24.950 --> 01:03:26.570
and calculate it
for you so you don't

01:03:26.570 --> 01:03:30.750
have to walk through
the expressions

01:03:30.750 --> 01:03:32.000
that we just walked through.

01:03:32.000 --> 01:03:35.000
It is easy.

01:03:35.000 --> 01:03:37.110
In other words, you
plug something in.

01:03:37.110 --> 01:03:38.160
You get some ray traces.

01:03:38.160 --> 01:03:40.830
You can calculate reflectance
and so forth, transmittance.

01:03:40.830 --> 01:03:43.424
But it's as smart as
what you put into it.

01:03:43.424 --> 01:03:45.590
It's really important to
understand the fundamentals

01:03:45.590 --> 01:03:48.590
behind any simulation software
because you will get out

01:03:48.590 --> 01:03:50.410
of it what you put into it.

01:03:50.410 --> 01:03:52.840
You will not be able to
pick up on obvious things

01:03:52.840 --> 01:03:55.890
that you might of--
for example, double

01:03:55.890 --> 01:03:57.390
clicked on this
little material here

01:03:57.390 --> 01:04:01.290
and find the real component of
the refractive index completely

01:04:01.290 --> 01:04:02.130
wrong.

01:04:02.130 --> 01:04:03.854
And you might not notice it.

01:04:03.854 --> 01:04:05.270
You might not pick
up on it if you

01:04:05.270 --> 01:04:07.600
don't have some good
intuition which is

01:04:07.600 --> 01:04:09.410
grounded in the fundamentals.

01:04:09.410 --> 01:04:11.880
And so it's important
that you understand

01:04:11.880 --> 01:04:13.250
what we've presented today.

01:04:13.250 --> 01:04:15.624
It's important you understand
the reading and, of course,

01:04:15.624 --> 01:04:19.290
do the p-set as well to really
drive those fundamentals home.

01:04:19.290 --> 01:04:23.450
So to kind of put a big umbrella
over the entire lecture,

01:04:23.450 --> 01:04:28.630
light management ensures
that the absorbtance is high.

01:04:28.630 --> 01:04:31.790
The absorbtance would
be, essentially,

01:04:31.790 --> 01:04:33.833
the amount of light
getting absorbed inside

01:04:33.833 --> 01:04:38.160
of the material, normalized by
the amount of light going in,

01:04:38.160 --> 01:04:39.370
so 1 minus r.

01:04:39.370 --> 01:04:43.910
So we want to ensure that
light enters the absorber.

01:04:43.910 --> 01:04:45.516
We want to minimize reflection.

01:04:45.516 --> 01:04:48.015
We want to ensure good light
trapping inside of the absorber

01:04:48.015 --> 01:04:50.930
as well, the absorber
being the material,

01:04:50.930 --> 01:04:53.347
our photovoltaic material, the
ones absorbing the sunlight

01:04:53.347 --> 01:04:55.388
and ultimately going to
be generating the charge.

01:04:55.388 --> 01:04:56.540
So we call it the absorber.

01:04:56.540 --> 01:04:58.540
So we want to ensure good
light trapping inside it.

01:04:58.540 --> 01:05:00.414
We want to ensure the
maximum amount of light

01:05:00.414 --> 01:05:01.780
gets trapped inside.

01:05:01.780 --> 01:05:04.662
We want to maximize the
optical path length within it.

01:05:04.662 --> 01:05:06.120
And we want to
minimize reflectance

01:05:06.120 --> 01:05:08.280
off the front surface.

01:05:08.280 --> 01:05:10.530
There are fancier ways of
light management as well

01:05:10.530 --> 01:05:12.570
that don't involve light
trapping necessarily

01:05:12.570 --> 01:05:16.930
but light manipulation or even
semiconductor manipulation.

01:05:16.930 --> 01:05:20.600
You can, for instance,
change the wave length

01:05:20.600 --> 01:05:23.370
of the incoming light.

01:05:23.370 --> 01:05:25.000
One very simple
example of this is

01:05:25.000 --> 01:05:27.750
when you shine, say for
example, red light on a phosphor

01:05:27.750 --> 01:05:30.290
and then it glows
green in the dark.

01:05:30.290 --> 01:05:32.250
That's a wavelength
change-- maybe not red.

01:05:32.250 --> 01:05:35.650
You'd probably have to shine
blue to have it glow green.

01:05:35.650 --> 01:05:38.125
That's an example of a
spectral down converter where

01:05:38.125 --> 01:05:39.500
it's taking a
higher energy light

01:05:39.500 --> 01:05:41.782
and converting it into
lower energy light.

01:05:41.782 --> 01:05:43.240
Likewise, there
are folks out there

01:05:43.240 --> 01:05:45.570
trying to do spectral up
converters where they take

01:05:45.570 --> 01:05:48.210
two lower energy photons
then somehow convert that

01:05:48.210 --> 01:05:50.280
into a higher energy photon.

01:05:50.280 --> 01:05:52.970
And so since our
absorption coefficient

01:05:52.970 --> 01:05:54.740
is dependent on
wavelength, if we're

01:05:54.740 --> 01:05:57.350
able to shift the wavelength
of the light around

01:05:57.350 --> 01:05:59.540
by engineering materials
near the surface,

01:05:59.540 --> 01:06:01.230
we can enhance
absorption as well.

01:06:01.230 --> 01:06:03.470
That is a form-- a valid
form-- of light management.

01:06:03.470 --> 01:06:05.780
It has additional
benefits as well.

01:06:05.780 --> 01:06:08.330
If we can eliminate the longer
wavelength stuff out here,

01:06:08.330 --> 01:06:11.760
which is heat, performance
of most solar cell

01:06:11.760 --> 01:06:13.570
suffers when they get hot.

01:06:13.570 --> 01:06:15.300
And we'll learn why
that is about five

01:06:15.300 --> 01:06:16.700
or 10 lectures from now.

01:06:16.700 --> 01:06:19.190
And so if we manage to
do spectral up converting

01:06:19.190 --> 01:06:22.660
or reflect that long wavelength
light away from our device,

01:06:22.660 --> 01:06:24.526
we can improve
performance there as well.

01:06:24.526 --> 01:06:26.150
That's another form
of light management

01:06:26.150 --> 01:06:30.370
that doesn't necessarily
involve light trapping.

01:06:30.370 --> 01:06:34.050
So again, I wanted
to really emphasize

01:06:34.050 --> 01:06:36.990
that light management
is necessary devices.

01:06:36.990 --> 01:06:39.837
This is no light
trapping, the blue curve,

01:06:39.837 --> 01:06:42.420
and with light trapping, light
trapping being essentially just

01:06:42.420 --> 01:06:45.495
an engineered coating
on the backside,

01:06:45.495 --> 01:06:47.620
on the backside of your
device, of lights coming in

01:06:47.620 --> 01:06:48.209
through here.

01:06:48.209 --> 01:06:49.750
I've engineered a
coating on the back

01:06:49.750 --> 01:06:52.660
to reflect the light back so
that it gets a second bounce

01:06:52.660 --> 01:06:53.594
through the material.

01:06:53.594 --> 01:06:55.010
I've engineered
the front surface,

01:06:55.010 --> 01:06:57.860
texturized it so that we have
not only the benefit of two

01:06:57.860 --> 01:07:00.930
bounces, double the
chance of light going in,

01:07:00.930 --> 01:07:04.370
but also the Snell's
Law working in our favor

01:07:04.370 --> 01:07:06.410
and increasing the
optical pathway.

01:07:06.410 --> 01:07:12.082
And so all told, the one
reason why this boost is so big

01:07:12.082 --> 01:07:14.290
right here is because I'm
increasing the optical path

01:07:14.290 --> 01:07:15.710
length, the effective
optical path

01:07:15.710 --> 01:07:18.770
length, relative to the
thickness of my material.

01:07:18.770 --> 01:07:22.610
And as a result, I'm getting
a much larger current output.

01:07:22.610 --> 01:07:24.902
I'm generating many
more free carriers

01:07:24.902 --> 01:07:25.860
instead of my material.

01:07:25.860 --> 01:07:27.720
I'm absorbing much
more light inside

01:07:27.720 --> 01:07:31.827
of my material, just a very
simple calculation versus cell

01:07:31.827 --> 01:07:32.800
thickness.

01:07:32.800 --> 01:07:34.841
And obviously the thicker
and thicker and thicker

01:07:34.841 --> 01:07:38.065
you go in your device, the
less important this becomes.

01:07:38.065 --> 01:07:40.190
Because the less important
light trapping-- I mean,

01:07:40.190 --> 01:07:41.600
you have the entire thickness.

01:07:41.600 --> 01:07:44.560
I can absorb the majority
of the light in one pass.

01:07:44.560 --> 01:07:48.730
But if you have
a thinner device,

01:07:48.730 --> 01:07:50.106
it really begins to matter.

01:07:50.106 --> 01:07:51.480
Once the thickness
of your device

01:07:51.480 --> 01:07:54.684
starts approaching the
optical absorption, or 1

01:07:54.684 --> 01:07:56.600
over the optical absorption
coefficient, which

01:07:56.600 --> 01:07:59.250
is the extension
length, then it really

01:07:59.250 --> 01:08:02.390
begins to matter in
the absorption length.

01:08:02.390 --> 01:08:05.170
Light trapping can still matter
for thick devices, though.

01:08:05.170 --> 01:08:10.830
Because if you manage to make
the light essentially refract

01:08:10.830 --> 01:08:14.330
or bend, if you will, so that
it travels near the surface,

01:08:14.330 --> 01:08:16.270
the distance that
those excited carriers

01:08:16.270 --> 01:08:18.454
have to travel to be
collected is shorter.

01:08:18.454 --> 01:08:21.240
And so you can get an additional
benefit from thicker devices

01:08:21.240 --> 01:08:22.823
by engineering light
trapping as well.

01:08:25.350 --> 01:08:27.535
OK, any questions about this?

01:08:27.535 --> 01:08:30.175
This is kind of important.

01:08:30.175 --> 01:08:32.300
This is why we spent all
this time in lecture today

01:08:32.300 --> 01:08:35.810
talking about light management
is because of this plot right

01:08:35.810 --> 01:08:36.970
here.

01:08:36.970 --> 01:08:40.140
That's why.

01:08:40.140 --> 01:08:42.250
I just wanted to show
you a cross section

01:08:42.250 --> 01:08:43.679
of very high efficiency device.

01:08:43.679 --> 01:08:45.220
This is one of the
highest efficiency

01:08:45.220 --> 01:08:47.040
silicon-based devices
are out there.

01:08:47.040 --> 01:08:51.550
And we have these
so-called backside mirror,

01:08:51.550 --> 01:08:54.540
which is really just a layer
of dielectric material,

01:08:54.540 --> 01:08:56.420
typically, that
reflects the light off

01:08:56.420 --> 01:08:58.469
of that interface
using the equation

01:08:58.469 --> 01:09:00.260
that we saw at the very
beginning of class,

01:09:00.260 --> 01:09:05.500
the r equal to [INAUDIBLE]
n minus 1 quantity squared

01:09:05.500 --> 01:09:09.770
divided by open parentheses
n plus 1 quantity squared.

01:09:09.770 --> 01:09:12.680
So that's benefiting here from
the change of refractive index

01:09:12.680 --> 01:09:15.060
going through your silicon
to that dielectric material

01:09:15.060 --> 01:09:17.609
in the back.

01:09:17.609 --> 01:09:19.420
They definitely take
good advantage of it.

01:09:19.420 --> 01:09:20.420
Where you have
your metal, you're

01:09:20.420 --> 01:09:21.439
going to be absorbing the light.

01:09:21.439 --> 01:09:23.730
Or you have a higher probability
of absorbing the light

01:09:23.730 --> 01:09:26.470
than you would if you had
a dielectric semiconductor

01:09:26.470 --> 01:09:27.630
interface.

01:09:27.630 --> 01:09:29.950
So the device design can
get pretty complicated

01:09:29.950 --> 01:09:32.740
for these super high
efficiency devices.

01:09:32.740 --> 01:09:36.149
And they're worried quite a bit
about trapping, other things

01:09:36.149 --> 01:09:36.649
as well.

01:09:36.649 --> 01:09:38.630
AUDIENCE: Coefficient,
is that one there?

01:09:38.630 --> 01:09:40.490
TONIO BUONASSISI:
This one right here?

01:09:40.490 --> 01:09:46.890
In the lab, 24.2%, in commercial
production, 22% and change.

01:09:46.890 --> 01:09:50.580
22.4%, I think.

01:09:50.580 --> 01:09:53.200
Just to throw some
last things out there

01:09:53.200 --> 01:09:55.790
since we're five
minutes to closure.

01:09:55.790 --> 01:09:59.880
Snell's Law assumes that there's
no phase shift of the light

01:09:59.880 --> 01:10:02.174
as it transfers from
one medium to another.

01:10:02.174 --> 01:10:03.715
If you introduce a
phase shift-- this

01:10:03.715 --> 01:10:06.015
is just a paper published
in Science last week

01:10:06.015 --> 01:10:08.670
by our friends over at
Harvard, Federico Capasso.

01:10:08.670 --> 01:10:10.660
If you introduce a
phase shift of the light

01:10:10.660 --> 01:10:12.368
as it goes through
one medium or another,

01:10:12.368 --> 01:10:14.280
now you can start
doing some fun things.

01:10:14.280 --> 01:10:18.530
If you introduce a constant
phase shift gradient

01:10:18.530 --> 01:10:21.540
throughout the surface of a
material, let's say right here,

01:10:21.540 --> 01:10:23.970
then you can cause
each node, each point

01:10:23.970 --> 01:10:27.140
within your material, to
lag by an increasing amount,

01:10:27.140 --> 01:10:29.900
so that your wave
front now bends.

01:10:29.900 --> 01:10:33.410
You can think of these as kind
of a Huygen wavefront forming

01:10:33.410 --> 01:10:35.950
as a result of these
small nodes here.

01:10:35.950 --> 01:10:38.570
And if you can tailor
the phase independently

01:10:38.570 --> 01:10:41.805
at each one of these points, you
can cause an increasing delay

01:10:41.805 --> 01:10:43.209
as you go across.

01:10:43.209 --> 01:10:45.000
And that will cause
the light, essentially,

01:10:45.000 --> 01:10:48.290
if you trace through the
points of maximum intensity,

01:10:48.290 --> 01:10:51.432
say the pink, you'll see
that the light is bent.

01:10:51.432 --> 01:10:52.390
And that's pretty cool.

01:10:52.390 --> 01:10:56.100
Because now we
